Dialogue: 0,0:00:01.58,0:00:03.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Greetings! \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:03.59,0:00:06.79,Default,,0,0,0,,We’re so happy you could join us \Nfor this broadcast. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:06.79,0:00:10.13,Default,,0,0,0,,And I’m very happy \Nbecause my cohost this month \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:10.13,0:00:14.13,Default,,0,0,0,,is a good friend of mine \Nand a fellow worker, Brother Jim Mantz. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:14.13,0:00:17.30,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, Jim and I work together \Nin the Writing Department, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:17.30,0:00:20.24,Default,,0,0,0,,and Jim helps the Writing Department\N—Jim and his team. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:20.24,0:00:22.24,Default,,0,0,0,,They help the Writing Department \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:22.24,0:00:25.24,Default,,0,0,0,,to keep track of all the projects \Nthat we have to work on. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:25.24,0:00:28.11,Default,,0,0,0,,And do you have any idea how many that is? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:28.11,0:00:31.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Two hundred and forty-one at any given time. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:31.95,0:00:35.12,Default,,0,0,0,,And Jim does a lot of other things as well. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:35.12,0:00:38.22,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, Jim, \Nwe’ve got another project on hand this month, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:38.22,0:00:40.76,Default,,0,0,0,,and that’s to get this broadcast under way. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:40.76,0:00:45.63,Default,,0,0,0,,So why don’t you tell the folks at home \Njust what they have to look forward to?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:45.63,0:00:49.37,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, David, this month \Nwe’ll get acquainted with a family \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:49.37,0:00:53.00,Default,,0,0,0,,that raised their children \Nto put Jehovah first in their lives. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:54.07,0:00:57.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s look for points \Nwe can apply in our families. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:58.27,0:01:00.61,Default,,0,0,0,,Later, our music video \Nwill emphasize the need \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:00.61,0:01:05.72,Default,,0,0,0,,to take the time to marvel \Nat Jehovah’s creation. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:05.72,0:01:09.09,Default,,0,0,0,,And we’ll visit \Nthe Writing Research Department. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:09.09,0:01:11.09,Default,,0,0,0,,The brothers and sisters there \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:11.09,0:01:14.22,Default,,0,0,0,,help us to ensure that all our articles \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:14.22,0:01:16.53,Default,,0,0,0,,and videos are accurate.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:16.53,0:01:18.70,Default,,0,0,0,,You’re going to enjoy this program, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:18.70,0:01:22.47,Default,,0,0,0,,and this is the November 2017 program \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:22.47,0:01:25.00,Default,,0,0,0,,of JW Broadcasting!\N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:42.85,0:01:45.79,Default,,0,0,0,,This month I’d like to talk about the efforts \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:45.79,0:01:47.79,Default,,0,0,0,,Jehovah’s organization is making \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:47.79,0:01:51.19,Default,,0,0,0,,to produce literature, publications, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:51.19,0:01:55.37,Default,,0,0,0,,articles that are as accurate as possible. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:55.37,0:02:00.37,Default,,0,0,0,,We’re going to talk about accuracy\N—accuracy of statement. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:00.37,0:02:06.01,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, first, what’s the responsibility \Nof the writer of the article? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:06.01,0:02:09.05,Default,,0,0,0,,When a writer submits \Nan article for publication, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:09.05,0:02:13.72,Default,,0,0,0,,he is expected to supply references \Nfrom reputable sources \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:13.72,0:02:16.49,Default,,0,0,0,,to back up the facts \Nthat he’s included in his article. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:16.49,0:02:19.26,Default,,0,0,0,,And our Research Department \Nwill use those references \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:19.26,0:02:22.19,Default,,0,0,0,,to check the accuracy of everything.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:22.19,0:02:25.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Reliable, respected sources. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:25.60,0:02:29.03,Default,,0,0,0,,What do we mean by a reliable source? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:29.03,0:02:32.34,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, first of all, we go with encyclopedias, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:32.34,0:02:37.34,Default,,0,0,0,,books, magazines, and then newspapers\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:37.34,0:02:39.48,Default,,0,0,0,,—basically in that order. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:39.48,0:02:42.75,Default,,0,0,0,,We prefer encyclopedias over books, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:42.75,0:02:45.35,Default,,0,0,0,,books over magazines, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:45.35,0:02:47.38,Default,,0,0,0,,and magazines over newspapers\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:47.38,0:02:50.95,Default,,0,0,0,,—generally because newspaper editors \Nhave a hard time checking their facts. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:50.95,0:02:54.89,Default,,0,0,0,,They have a very limited time \Nin which to check their facts. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:54.89,0:02:58.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Even encyclopedias and books get updated, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:58.70,0:03:02.10,Default,,0,0,0,,so we have to go \Nwith the latest edition of those. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:02.10,0:03:06.10,Default,,0,0,0,,We have to make sure \Nthat our sources are reliable.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:06.10,0:03:09.17,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, when a writer quotes an expert, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:09.17,0:03:12.78,Default,,0,0,0,,our researchers will ask: \N“Who’s this expert? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:12.78,0:03:14.78,Default,,0,0,0,,“What’s his reputation? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:14.78,0:03:17.98,Default,,0,0,0,,“Is he working for a particular organization? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:17.98,0:03:21.22,Default,,0,0,0,,“Does this organization have an agenda? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:21.22,0:03:23.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Is it a special-interest group?” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:23.42,0:03:27.49,Default,,0,0,0,,If we find that the goals \Nof the organization are questionable, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:27.49,0:03:32.00,Default,,0,0,0,,we won’t use the quote\N—even if it’s a really good quote.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:33.06,0:03:37.17,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, suppose that a writer \Nwants to quote something from a book. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:37.17,0:03:39.20,Default,,0,0,0,,In the reference material, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:39.20,0:03:42.41,Default,,0,0,0,,he’ll supply a photocopy \Nof the quote in the book, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:42.41,0:03:46.41,Default,,0,0,0,,but very often he’ll give us \Ntwo or three pages before the quote \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:46.41,0:03:49.31,Default,,0,0,0,,and two or three pages after as well. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:49.31,0:03:52.52,Default,,0,0,0,,And that way, \Nour researchers can examine the quote \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:52.52,0:03:56.62,Default,,0,0,0,,in context to make sure \Nthat what we’re saying in print \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:56.62,0:04:00.32,Default,,0,0,0,,is really what the author \Nof the quote had in mind.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:00.32,0:04:03.63,Default,,0,0,0,,For example, \Nan evolutionist might make a statement \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:03.63,0:04:05.63,Default,,0,0,0,,which on the surface \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:05.63,0:04:09.30,Default,,0,0,0,,appears to confirm his support of creation. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:09.30,0:04:11.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Or perhaps an atheist will make a statement \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:11.57,0:04:15.07,Default,,0,0,0,,that seems to indicate \Nthat he believes in God. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:15.07,0:04:17.47,Default,,0,0,0,,But when you examine \Nthe quote in context, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:17.47,0:04:21.44,Default,,0,0,0,,you realize that that isn’t what \Nthe author had in mind at all. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:21.44,0:04:25.72,Default,,0,0,0,,We would never \Ndeliberately distort a quotation. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:25.72,0:04:30.00,Default,,0,0,0,,We try very hard to use all \Nof our quotations in context.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:31.52,0:04:35.19,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, it’s important to keep up \Nwith the very latest research. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:35.19,0:04:39.83,Default,,0,0,0,,Something that was stated years ago \Nas a fact may have been disproved. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:39.83,0:04:41.86,Default,,0,0,0,,And the reason why is obvious. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:41.86,0:04:44.03,Default,,0,0,0,,Someone may spend his entire life \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:44.03,0:04:47.87,Default,,0,0,0,,researching a very limited point in history\N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:47.87,0:04:49.87,Default,,0,0,0,,—a very small point in history—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:49.87,0:04:52.08,Default,,0,0,0,,and, of course, \Nif he spends so much time researching, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:52.08,0:04:54.08,Default,,0,0,0,,he’s going to uncover things. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:54.08,0:04:56.58,Default,,0,0,0,,And so it’s not surprising \Nthat from time to time \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:56.58,0:05:00.72,Default,,0,0,0,,we have to adjust our view \Nof some historical points. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:00.72,0:05:03.22,Default,,0,0,0,,We have to check, check, check. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:03.22,0:05:07.49,Default,,0,0,0,,And later on in this discussion, \Nwe’re going to consider some examples of it. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:07.49,0:05:10.19,Default,,0,0,0,,It’ll be fun; you’ll love it!\N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:10.19,0:05:14.46,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, someone might ask, \N‘Why is it necessary to be so picky, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:14.46,0:05:18.20,Default,,0,0,0,,to be so fussy, about accuracy?’ \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:18.20,0:05:21.44,Default,,0,0,0,,And in answer, \NI’d like to give an experience \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:21.44,0:05:23.61,Default,,0,0,0,,that I heard about a few years ago. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:23.61,0:05:25.78,Default,,0,0,0,,In Northern Europe, \Nthere was a man \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:25.78,0:05:28.85,Default,,0,0,0,,who accepted a Bible study \Nfrom Jehovah’s Witnesses. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:28.85,0:05:30.85,Default,,0,0,0,,And when he was asked \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:30.85,0:05:33.65,Default,,0,0,0,,what motivated him \Nto want to study, he said: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:33.65,0:05:37.32,Default,,0,0,0,,“I read an article \Nin your Awake! magazine on trees. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:37.32,0:05:40.56,Default,,0,0,0,,“Now, I happen to be \Na bit of an expert on trees. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:40.56,0:05:43.83,Default,,0,0,0,,“And after I read the article, \NI said to myself: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:43.83,0:05:47.10,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘That article was so well-documented. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:47.10,0:05:49.20,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘It was so precise. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:49.20,0:05:53.40,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘Any organization that is that careful \Nwhen writing about trees \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:53.40,0:05:56.91,Default,,0,0,0,,is going to be just as careful \Nwhen teaching me the Bible.’” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:56.91,0:06:00.00,Default,,0,0,0,,And on that basis, \Nhe accepted a Bible study.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:02.01,0:06:05.28,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, an area where great care \Nneeds to be taken \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:05.28,0:06:07.65,Default,,0,0,0,,is when we’re quoting statistics. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:07.65,0:06:10.99,Default,,0,0,0,,A newspaper may report on a disaster \Nin a certain country \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:10.99,0:06:15.76,Default,,0,0,0,,and say that 10,000 people \Nwere killed in the disaster. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:15.76,0:06:18.69,Default,,0,0,0,,Immediately, \Nour researchers are going to ask, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:18.69,0:06:21.13,Default,,0,0,0,,“Where did they get that statistic?” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:21.13,0:06:24.17,Default,,0,0,0,,They might phone the newspaper \Nand ask for the source. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:24.17,0:06:27.17,Default,,0,0,0,,And if the reporter \Ncan’t confirm the statistic, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:27.17,0:06:30.17,Default,,0,0,0,,our researchers will go to another source\N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:30.17,0:06:34.98,Default,,0,0,0,,—a more official source—\Nto get the correct statistic.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:34.98,0:06:38.88,Default,,0,0,0,,Care is also taken \Nwhen quoting personalities of the past. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:38.88,0:06:43.79,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, suppose we want to quote \Nsomething that Napoleon Bonaparte said\N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:43.79,0:06:45.79,Default,,0,0,0,,—the French general. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:45.79,0:06:49.46,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, being French, \NNapoleon spoke French. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:49.46,0:06:51.46,Default,,0,0,0,,So if we’re quoting it in English, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:51.46,0:06:56.13,Default,,0,0,0,,that means that somebody translated \Nthe quote from French into English. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:56.13,0:06:59.94,Default,,0,0,0,,But did they translate the quote correctly? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:59.94,0:07:04.14,Default,,0,0,0,,Our researchers will probably go \Nto the target language \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:04.14,0:07:08.68,Default,,0,0,0,,and research the quote \Nin French or in another language. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:08.68,0:07:13.65,Default,,0,0,0,,And more often than not, \Nthey find that what is presented in English \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:13.65,0:07:18.00,Default,,0,0,0,,doesn’t accurately represent \Nwhat the individual said at all.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:19.19,0:07:22.83,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, as we age, \Nour memory can play tricks on us. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:22.83,0:07:25.00,Default,,0,0,0,,And our researchers are aware of that. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:26.30,0:07:29.13,Default,,0,0,0,,Suppose that an elderly brother \Nwrites in his life story \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:29.13,0:07:33.90,Default,,0,0,0,,that he was baptized \Nat a circuit assembly on a certain date. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:33.90,0:07:36.77,Default,,0,0,0,,Our researchers may look at the date. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:36.77,0:07:38.77,Default,,0,0,0,,They may check the date, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:38.77,0:07:43.01,Default,,0,0,0,,and suppose they find that the date \Nthe brother gave fell on a Tuesday. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:43.01,0:07:47.55,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, what are the chances that there was \Na circuit assembly on a Tuesday? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:47.55,0:07:50.29,Default,,0,0,0,,There may have been, \Nbut they’re going to check. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:50.29,0:07:53.29,Default,,0,0,0,,Is the brother’s memory failing him? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:53.29,0:07:55.32,Default,,0,0,0,,If they can’t confirm the date, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:55.32,0:07:57.56,Default,,0,0,0,,they may ask someone to help the brother \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:57.56,0:08:00.73,Default,,0,0,0,,to remember the date \Nmore correctly, more accurately. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:00.73,0:08:04.67,Default,,0,0,0,,Perhaps someone was baptized \Nat the same circuit assembly as he was, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:04.67,0:08:08.00,Default,,0,0,0,,and perhaps that person \Nhas an accurate note of the date.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:09.61,0:08:12.51,Default,,0,0,0,,Our translators also go to great lengths \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:12.51,0:08:16.95,Default,,0,0,0,,to present accurate information \Nto the brothers and sisters. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:16.95,0:08:19.75,Default,,0,0,0,,Some time ago, \Nthe Awake! magazine published an article \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:19.75,0:08:23.15,Default,,0,0,0,,on a very rare species of butterfly. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:23.15,0:08:25.92,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, with all animals and insects, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:25.92,0:08:28.19,Default,,0,0,0,,we provide our translators \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:28.19,0:08:31.29,Default,,0,0,0,,with the Latin name \Nof the animal or the insect. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:31.29,0:08:33.66,Default,,0,0,0,,And so our translators had the Latin name. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:33.66,0:08:35.67,Default,,0,0,0,,But in one large country, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:35.67,0:08:38.60,Default,,0,0,0,,they were unable to find \Nthe name in the vernacular. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:38.60,0:08:40.60,Default,,0,0,0,,So, what did they do? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:40.60,0:08:43.84,Default,,0,0,0,,They phoned the country’s leading university, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:43.84,0:08:46.84,Default,,0,0,0,,and they were transferred \Nto the Biology Department, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:46.84,0:08:48.91,Default,,0,0,0,,and there an expert gave them \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:48.91,0:08:52.78,Default,,0,0,0,,the name in the vernacular \Nof that particular butterfly. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:52.78,0:08:56.09,Default,,0,0,0,,But then he said: \N“Why is it that you’re worrying so much \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:56.09,0:08:58.32,Default,,0,0,0,,“about the correct name of this butterfly? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:58.32,0:09:00.79,Default,,0,0,0,,“If you got it wrong, \Nthere are only two of us \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:00.79,0:09:03.69,Default,,0,0,0,,in the whole country \Nwho would’ve known the difference.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:03.69,0:09:08.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, that opened the way \Nto give a witness to this expert.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:09.13,0:09:11.13,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, now, how well would you do \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:11.13,0:09:13.80,Default,,0,0,0,,in spotting a statement that is slightly off \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:13.80,0:09:16.07,Default,,0,0,0,,and making it more accurate? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:16.07,0:09:18.07,Default,,0,0,0,,Would you like to find out? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:18.07,0:09:20.58,Default,,0,0,0,,Of course you would! \NIt’ll be fun. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:20.58,0:09:22.78,Default,,0,0,0,,So let’s take a quiz that I’ll call \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:22.78,0:09:24.88,Default,,0,0,0,,You Be the Editor. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:24.88,0:09:27.82,Default,,0,0,0,,We’re going to put \Na number of statements on the screen, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:27.82,0:09:30.45,Default,,0,0,0,,and there’s a problem \Nwith each one of them. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:30.45,0:09:33.46,Default,,0,0,0,,Now your job \Nis to figure out what’s wrong, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:33.46,0:09:37.46,Default,,0,0,0,,why it is wrong, \Nand then suggest how to fix it. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:37.46,0:09:39.46,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s going to be fun.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:39.46,0:09:41.46,Default,,0,0,0,,Here’s the first statement: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:41.46,0:09:45.53,Default,,0,0,0,,“According \Nto the Smithsonian Knowledge Encyclopedia, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:45.53,0:09:47.57,Default,,0,0,0,,“the Egyptian Sphinx \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:47.57,0:09:51.94,Default,,0,0,0,,was constructed around 2550 B.C.E.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:51.94,0:09:54.58,Default,,0,0,0,,“The Egyptian Sphinx \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:54.58,0:09:58.91,Default,,0,0,0,,was constructed around 2550 B.C.E.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:58.91,0:10:00.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, the problem \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:00.95,0:10:03.42,Default,,0,0,0,,is with the date 2550 B.C.E. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:03.42,0:10:05.42,Default,,0,0,0,,The global Flood occurred \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:05.42,0:10:08.32,Default,,0,0,0,,about 200 years after that date. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:08.32,0:10:12.76,Default,,0,0,0,,So, what are the chances \Nthat the Sphinx survived the Flood? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:12.76,0:10:16.77,Default,,0,0,0,,Unless, of course, you think \Nthat’s how the Sphinx lost his nose. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:16.77,0:10:19.87,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, these dates \Nare good for you school children \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:19.87,0:10:21.97,Default,,0,0,0,,to keep in mind \Nwhen you’re writing reports. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:21.97,0:10:24.54,Default,,0,0,0,,Sometimes you copy something \Nfrom an encyclopedia, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:24.54,0:10:26.54,Default,,0,0,0,,and it gives a certain date. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:26.54,0:10:29.88,Default,,0,0,0,,But think about the date of the Flood,\N2370 B.C.E.,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:29.88,0:10:34.00,Default,,0,0,0,,so that what you put in your report \Nis as accurate as possible.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:36.32,0:10:38.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Now let’s go on to the next one: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:38.95,0:10:40.96,Default,,0,0,0,,“In 29 C.E., \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:40.96,0:10:44.53,Default,,0,0,0,,“Jesus was baptized by a close relative, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:44.53,0:10:47.00,Default,,0,0,0,,John the Baptizer.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:48.13,0:10:50.67,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, 29 C.E., that looks right. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:50.67,0:10:52.67,Default,,0,0,0,,And we know that Jesus \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:52.67,0:10:54.84,Default,,0,0,0,,was baptized by John; that’s right. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:54.84,0:10:56.87,Default,,0,0,0,,So the problem must be \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:56.87,0:10:59.98,Default,,0,0,0,,“close relative,” and it is. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:59.98,0:11:02.35,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, both of Jesus’ parents \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:02.35,0:11:07.05,Default,,0,0,0,,were of the tribe of Judah, \Nand their parents were of the tribe of Judah. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:07.05,0:11:10.72,Default,,0,0,0,,But, what about John’s parents, \NZechariah and Elizabeth? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:10.72,0:11:12.92,Default,,0,0,0,,They were both of the tribe of Levi. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:12.92,0:11:15.59,Default,,0,0,0,,So Elizabeth and Mary \Ncouldn’t have been sisters. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:15.59,0:11:17.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Could they have been cousins? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:17.63,0:11:18.73,Default,,0,0,0,,Maybe. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:18.73,0:11:20.73,Default,,0,0,0,,We can’t even confirm that. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:20.73,0:11:24.90,Default,,0,0,0,,And if they were, that would make \NJesus and John second cousins. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:24.90,0:11:28.17,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, is a second cousin a “close relative”? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:28.17,0:11:30.74,Default,,0,0,0,,Some would say yes; \Nsome would say no. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:30.74,0:11:33.31,Default,,0,0,0,,So it’s safer just to say, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:33.31,0:11:37.61,Default,,0,0,0,,“In 29 C.E., \NJesus was baptized by a relative, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:37.61,0:11:40.32,Default,,0,0,0,,John the Baptizer.”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:40.32,0:11:41.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Here’s one. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:41.42,0:11:44.19,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s see if you can spot \Nthe error in this one: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:44.19,0:11:46.19,Default,,0,0,0,,“While most of the early Christians \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:46.19,0:11:48.96,Default,,0,0,0,,“were held in little esteem in the community, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:48.96,0:11:52.36,Default,,0,0,0,,“a few enjoyed an elevated social status. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:52.36,0:11:57.90,Default,,0,0,0,,For example, Luke was a respected physician.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:57.90,0:11:59.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, the word we need \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:59.57,0:12:02.27,Default,,0,0,0,,to look at is “respected.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:02.27,0:12:05.01,Default,,0,0,0,,We respect our doctors today, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:05.01,0:12:08.41,Default,,0,0,0,,and our doctors have \Na very, very fine education. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:08.41,0:12:11.25,Default,,0,0,0,,But was that the case in the first century? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:11.25,0:12:15.72,Default,,0,0,0,,A reference work says this \Nabout first-century physicians: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:15.72,0:12:19.22,Default,,0,0,0,,“Many doctors were freed Greek slaves, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:19.22,0:12:23.73,Default,,0,0,0,,“hence the social standing \Nof doctors was quite low. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:23.73,0:12:26.63,Default,,0,0,0,,“Because recovery rates were so low, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:26.63,0:12:30.40,Default,,0,0,0,,many people were skeptical \Nor even scornful of doctors.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:30.40,0:12:33.27,Default,,0,0,0,,Note this statement from the first century: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:33.27,0:12:36.87,Default,,0,0,0,,“Until recently, Diaulus was a doctor; \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:36.87,0:12:39.71,Default,,0,0,0,,“now he is an undertaker. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:39.71,0:12:41.98,Default,,0,0,0,,“He is still doing as an undertaker, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:41.98,0:12:44.98,Default,,0,0,0,,what he used to do as a doctor.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:44.98,0:12:46.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Not very flattering, is it? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:46.98,0:12:51.22,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, in this case, we’d probably have to use \Na different example.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:51.22,0:12:52.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Here’s one: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:52.76,0:12:55.83,Default,,0,0,0,,“In 325 C.E., \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:55.83,0:12:57.83,Default,,0,0,0,,“the Roman Emperor Constantine \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:57.83,0:12:59.86,Default,,0,0,0,,“established Christianity \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:59.86,0:13:01.86,Default,,0,0,0,,“as the official religion \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:01.86,0:13:04.83,Default,,0,0,0,,of the Roman Empire.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:04.83,0:13:08.17,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, 325 C.E., that looks right. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:08.17,0:13:11.17,Default,,0,0,0,,And Constantine, that looks right. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:11.17,0:13:13.54,Default,,0,0,0,,But look at the word “official”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:13.54,0:13:16.75,Default,,0,0,0,,—“official religion.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:16.75,0:13:19.78,Default,,0,0,0,,Constantine never established Christianity \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:19.78,0:13:23.05,Default,,0,0,0,,as the official religion \Nof the Roman Empire. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:23.05,0:13:26.82,Default,,0,0,0,,In 313 B.C.E., \Nhe did make it legal to be a Christian, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:26.82,0:13:29.73,Default,,0,0,0,,but paganism was still \None of the official religions. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:29.73,0:13:33.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Apostate Christianity \Ndidn’t become the official religion \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:33.70,0:13:37.00,Default,,0,0,0,,until 391 C.E.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:37.00,0:13:39.00,Default,,0,0,0,,This one is tricky. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:39.00,0:13:41.37,Default,,0,0,0,,See how you do with this one: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:41.37,0:13:43.37,Default,,0,0,0,,“Imagine the apostle Paul \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:43.37,0:13:46.18,Default,,0,0,0,,“during his first imprisonment in Rome, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:46.18,0:13:48.44,Default,,0,0,0,,“writing his letter to the Colossians \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:48.44,0:13:51.00,Default,,0,0,0,,from a dark prison cell.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:52.11,0:13:54.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, if you look in the back \Nof the New World Translation, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:54.42,0:13:58.09,Default,,0,0,0,,you’ll find that Paul did write his letter \Nto the Colossians while in Rome, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:58.09,0:14:01.69,Default,,0,0,0,,and he was imprisoned at the time. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:01.69,0:14:04.06,Default,,0,0,0,,So, what’s the problem? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:04.06,0:14:06.36,Default,,0,0,0,,“Dark prison cell.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:06.36,0:14:09.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Where was Paul \Nduring his first imprisonment? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:09.20,0:14:11.83,Default,,0,0,0,,In his own rented house. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:11.83,0:14:14.10,Default,,0,0,0,,So the statement “dark prison cell,” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:14.10,0:14:18.21,Default,,0,0,0,,it’s very dramatic, but it’s all wrong.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:18.21,0:14:20.78,Default,,0,0,0,,Here’s an old one: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:20.78,0:14:22.78,Default,,0,0,0,,“While Paul generally preached \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:22.78,0:14:24.78,Default,,0,0,0,,“to people of the nations, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:24.78,0:14:26.85,Default,,0,0,0,,“Peter was sent to the Jews. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:26.85,0:14:29.42,Default,,0,0,0,,“Contrary to popular belief, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:29.42,0:14:32.32,Default,,0,0,0,,Peter was never in Rome.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:32.32,0:14:34.99,Default,,0,0,0,,Some scholars used to make that statement, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:34.99,0:14:37.16,Default,,0,0,0,,and they made it 60 years ago: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:37.16,0:14:40.06,Default,,0,0,0,,“Peter was never in Rome.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:40.06,0:14:42.06,Default,,0,0,0,,But can we really say that? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:42.06,0:14:44.27,Default,,0,0,0,,Can we be that dogmatic? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:44.27,0:14:46.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Can we say that he didn’t even spend \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:46.84,0:14:49.14,Default,,0,0,0,,vacation time or have a short visit in Rome? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:49.14,0:14:51.17,Default,,0,0,0,,No, we cannot. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:51.17,0:14:53.24,Default,,0,0,0,,So it would be more accurate to state: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:53.24,0:14:58.58,Default,,0,0,0,,“There is no record \Nthat Peter ever lived in Rome.”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:58.58,0:15:00.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Here’s one: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:00.38,0:15:03.09,Default,,0,0,0,,“We can have confidence in the Bible\N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:03.09,0:15:06.59,Default,,0,0,0,,—it is mankind’s oldest book.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:06.59,0:15:10.43,Default,,0,0,0,,“Mankind’s oldest book.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:10.43,0:15:13.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Years ago, some scholars believed \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:13.20,0:15:16.83,Default,,0,0,0,,that texts written \Nby Adam, Noah, and others \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:16.83,0:15:19.30,Default,,0,0,0,,survived the Flood \Nand became part of the Bible. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:19.30,0:15:21.30,Default,,0,0,0,,And if that were true, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:21.30,0:15:25.94,Default,,0,0,0,,then we could say that the Bible \Nis mankind’s oldest book. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:25.94,0:15:28.18,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, here’s a quote \Nfrom Insight on the Scriptures, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:28.18,0:15:30.21,Default,,0,0,0,,our Bible encyclopedia. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:30.21,0:15:34.52,Default,,0,0,0,,It says: \N“There is no way to establish definitely \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:34.52,0:15:37.32,Default,,0,0,0,,“that some of the histories \Nmentioned in the book of Genesis \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:37.32,0:15:40.59,Default,,0,0,0,,were committed to writing \Nbefore the Flood.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:40.59,0:15:44.86,Default,,0,0,0,,So, today we might call the Bible \None of mankind’s oldest books \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:44.86,0:15:48.36,Default,,0,0,0,,or the world’s oldest modern book, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:48.36,0:15:50.90,Default,,0,0,0,,as we do in one of our videos.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:50.90,0:15:53.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Here’s the last one: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:53.00,0:15:55.20,Default,,0,0,0,,“In 1517, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:55.20,0:15:58.64,Default,,0,0,0,,“Martin Luther nailed his 95 theses \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:58.64,0:16:02.00,Default,,0,0,0,,on the door of a church \Nin Wittenberg, Germany.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:03.68,0:16:05.85,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, we’ve highlighted “95,” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:05.85,0:16:08.78,Default,,0,0,0,,but there are questions \Nabout the entire statement. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:08.78,0:16:11.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Some modern scholars have done \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:11.42,0:16:14.42,Default,,0,0,0,,a tremendous, exhaustive study \Nof the life of Martin Luther, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:14.42,0:16:17.13,Default,,0,0,0,,and they claim \Nthat he couldn’t have compiled \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:17.13,0:16:21.80,Default,,0,0,0,,all 95 of his theses by 1517. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:21.80,0:16:25.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Others go so far as to claim \Nthat it never happened\N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:25.57,0:16:29.47,Default,,0,0,0,,—that he never did nail his theses \Non the door of the church. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:29.47,0:16:32.88,Default,,0,0,0,,Still others are just as adamant \Nthat it’s all true\N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:32.88,0:16:34.91,Default,,0,0,0,,—that it all happened. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:34.91,0:16:37.18,Default,,0,0,0,,So there’s no consensus. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:37.18,0:16:39.65,Default,,0,0,0,,We would have to modify the statement\N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:39.65,0:16:42.52,Default,,0,0,0,,—“some believe” or “it is believed”—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:42.52,0:16:44.52,Default,,0,0,0,,in order to make it more accurate \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:44.52,0:16:48.00,Default,,0,0,0,,and to acknowledge the fact \Nthat there are differences of opinion.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:49.83,0:16:52.73,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, how did you do on the quiz? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:52.73,0:16:57.47,Default,,0,0,0,,If you’re like me, you’ve probably made \Nsome of those statements yourself at times. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:57.47,0:17:01.30,Default,,0,0,0,,The statements were based \Non the best research we had at the time. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:01.30,0:17:04.74,Default,,0,0,0,,But this is to illustrate \Nthe fact that times change; \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:04.74,0:17:07.74,Default,,0,0,0,,research facilities improve. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:07.74,0:17:12.41,Default,,0,0,0,,A scholar does exhaustive research \Non one point of history, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:12.41,0:17:15.72,Default,,0,0,0,,and he uncovers things \Nthat were previously unknown. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:15.72,0:17:17.72,Default,,0,0,0,,So we have to keep up. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:17.72,0:17:20.19,Default,,0,0,0,,We have to check, check, check. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:20.19,0:17:24.33,Default,,0,0,0,,And when credible research \Nreveals that we have to adjust \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:24.33,0:17:26.96,Default,,0,0,0,,or tweak a statement \Nthat we made in the past, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:26.96,0:17:29.50,Default,,0,0,0,,we do so without hesitation. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:29.50,0:17:34.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Our goal is to provide information \Nthat is as accurate as possible \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:34.50,0:17:37.84,Default,,0,0,0,,because we know that you \Nbrothers and sisters use this information. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:37.84,0:17:39.84,Default,,0,0,0,,You quote it in the field ministry. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:39.84,0:17:41.91,Default,,0,0,0,,You use it in your public talks. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:41.91,0:17:44.45,Default,,0,0,0,,So we want to make sure \Nthat our brothers are fed \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:44.45,0:17:48.58,Default,,0,0,0,,with the most accurate \Nspiritual food possible.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:48.58,0:17:52.29,Default,,0,0,0,,We’re imperfect, of course, \Nand we are going to make mistakes. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:52.29,0:17:55.06,Default,,0,0,0,,And when we do, \Nwe have to correct them. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:55.06,0:18:00.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Our goal is to do the best we can \Nin all our imperfection.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:01.30,0:18:03.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, how does it make you feel? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:03.63,0:18:06.14,Default,,0,0,0,,I know how it makes me feel. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:06.14,0:18:11.14,Default,,0,0,0,,I’m grateful that Jehovah’s organization \Ntakes accuracy so seriously. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:11.14,0:18:13.34,Default,,0,0,0,,It gives me confidence. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:13.34,0:18:17.21,Default,,0,0,0,,And, you know, I’m reminded \Nof the description of another researcher, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:17.21,0:18:23.75,Default,,0,0,0,,as recorded at Ecclesiastes 12:9, 10. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:23.75,0:18:25.75,Default,,0,0,0,,You know who this is. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:25.75,0:18:30.19,Default,,0,0,0,,Ecclesiastes 12:9, 10: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:30.19,0:18:33.83,Default,,0,0,0,,“Not only had the congregator become wise \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:33.83,0:18:37.70,Default,,0,0,0,,“but he continually taught \Nthe people what he knew, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:37.70,0:18:40.04,Default,,0,0,0,,“and he pondered \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:40.04,0:18:43.37,Default,,0,0,0,,“and made a thorough search \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:43.37,0:18:46.34,Default,,0,0,0,,“in order to compile many proverbs. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:46.34,0:18:49.21,Default,,0,0,0,,“The congregator sought \Nto find delightful words \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:49.21,0:18:54.88,Default,,0,0,0,,and to record accurate words of truth.”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:54.88,0:18:59.09,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, let’s give our attention \Nto my good friend Jim. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:59.09,0:19:02.16,Default,,0,0,0,,And I think Jim is ready \Nto take us on a field trip \N
Dialogue: 0,0:19:02.16,0:19:04.63,Default,,0,0,0,,so we can meet \Nsome of the researchers at Bethel.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:19:04.63,0:19:05.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Thank you, David. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:19:05.63,0:19:09.97,Default,,0,0,0,,And, yes, our researchers take very seriously \N
Dialogue: 0,0:19:09.97,0:19:11.97,Default,,0,0,0,,their task of maintaining \N
Dialogue: 0,0:19:11.97,0:19:14.00,Default,,0,0,0,,a high standard of accuracy.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:19:17.94,0:19:22.14,Default,,0,0,0,,In today’s media, \Nmuch of what’s presented as fact \N
Dialogue: 0,0:19:22.14,0:19:26.00,Default,,0,0,0,,is often colored by emotion \Nand personal opinion.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:19:30.45,0:19:32.86,Default,,0,0,0,,Jehovah’s Witnesses, however, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:19:32.86,0:19:35.66,Default,,0,0,0,,remain committed \Nto defending God’s Word, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:19:35.66,0:19:38.33,Default,,0,0,0,,the Bible, as the standard for truth.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:19:38.33,0:19:41.03,Default,,0,0,0,,As Jesus said at John 17:17: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:19:41.03,0:19:43.00,Default,,0,0,0,,“Your word is truth.”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:19:44.17,0:19:46.17,Default,,0,0,0,,The wide-ranging subject matter \N
Dialogue: 0,0:19:46.17,0:19:49.14,Default,,0,0,0,,contained in the publications \Nof Jehovah’s Witnesses \N
Dialogue: 0,0:19:49.14,0:19:53.04,Default,,0,0,0,,is painstakingly researched \Nby their Writing Research Department. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:19:53.04,0:19:56.65,Default,,0,0,0,,Their research methods are modeled \Nafter that of Bible historians \N
Dialogue: 0,0:19:56.65,0:19:59.38,Default,,0,0,0,,such as Luke and Jeremiah\N
Dialogue: 0,0:19:59.38,0:20:02.00,Default,,0,0,0,,—reliance on reputable first-hand sources.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:05.29,0:20:07.02,Default,,0,0,0,,We’re not looking just for someone’s opinions \N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:07.02,0:20:08.69,Default,,0,0,0,,or what someone believes about a topic.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:08.69,0:20:10.69,Default,,0,0,0,,If the material is socially \N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:10.69,0:20:12.83,Default,,0,0,0,,or politically biased, for example, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:12.83,0:20:14.70,Default,,0,0,0,,we can’t rely on it. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:14.70,0:20:16.30,Default,,0,0,0,,We look for objective material.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:16.30,0:20:18.17,Default,,0,0,0,,We cover everything \N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:18.17,0:20:21.70,Default,,0,0,0,,from historical, scientific, geographical \N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:21.70,0:20:24.21,Default,,0,0,0,,to flora, fauna, space.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:24.21,0:20:26.21,Default,,0,0,0,,So before the script is even written, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:26.21,0:20:29.48,Default,,0,0,0,,we’ll provide a research package,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:29.48,0:20:31.78,Default,,0,0,0,,and we’ll follow\Nthe project until final delivery\N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:31.78,0:20:33.82,Default,,0,0,0,,to make sure\Nthat everything that is said\N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:33.82,0:20:35.78,Default,,0,0,0,,and everything that is shown\N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:35.78,0:20:37.29,Default,,0,0,0,,is solidly based on fact\N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:37.29,0:20:38.55,Default,,0,0,0,,and is well-researched.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:38.55,0:20:41.22,Default,,0,0,0,,There’s a lot more research than what \N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:41.22,0:20:44.09,Default,,0,0,0,,the viewer \Nor the reader will ever see.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:44.09,0:20:46.36,Default,,0,0,0,,You have a one-page article on the otter; \N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:46.36,0:20:48.23,Default,,0,0,0,,you end up with like 12 references \N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:48.23,0:20:50.87,Default,,0,0,0,,to back up every statement that’s made.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:50.87,0:20:52.03,Default,,0,0,0,,It seems very simple, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:52.03,0:20:53.60,Default,,0,0,0,,the height of Mont Blanc. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:53.60,0:20:55.40,Default,,0,0,0,,And with the height of Mont Blanc, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:55.40,0:20:59.31,Default,,0,0,0,,we found out, number one, \Nthat it was 4,807 meters; \N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:59.31,0:21:02.41,Default,,0,0,0,,then we found another source\N—4,810 meters; \N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:02.41,0:21:05.91,Default,,0,0,0,,let’s check a third one\N—4,808 meters. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:05.91,0:21:06.92,Default,,0,0,0,,So, what is now real? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:06.92,0:21:09.12,Default,,0,0,0,,In that case, we had to consult \N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:09.12,0:21:14.42,Default,,0,0,0,,the French National Institute \Nof Geographic and Forest Information.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:14.42,0:21:16.22,Default,,0,0,0,,One of our main research tools \N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:16.22,0:21:18.43,Default,,0,0,0,,is our own library system. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:18.43,0:21:23.00,Default,,0,0,0,,We have about 65,000 books \Nand other research materials.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:24.13,0:21:27.10,Default,,0,0,0,,If we’re researching something \Nabout ancient history \N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:27.10,0:21:29.57,Default,,0,0,0,,or archaeology, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:29.57,0:21:32.00,Default,,0,0,0,,we may consult \Na specialized encyclopedia, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:33.34,0:21:36.91,Default,,0,0,0,,like an encyclopedia \Nof archaeological discoveries, for example.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:36.91,0:21:39.78,Default,,0,0,0,,Museum websites usually have pictures \N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:39.78,0:21:41.48,Default,,0,0,0,,of what they have in the museum. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:41.48,0:21:44.25,Default,,0,0,0,,And we can find these visuals and then send \Nthose off to production teams \N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:44.25,0:21:46.79,Default,,0,0,0,,as well and say, \N“This is a good example \N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:46.79,0:21:48.32,Default,,0,0,0,,of a first-century lamp.”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:48.32,0:21:50.66,Default,,0,0,0,,Things that you think are true \N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:50.66,0:21:53.20,Default,,0,0,0,,because they are “commonly known” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:53.20,0:21:56.47,Default,,0,0,0,,may not actually be totally accurate.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:56.47,0:21:58.67,Default,,0,0,0,,Quotes need to be verified. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:58.67,0:22:02.20,Default,,0,0,0,,We want to go to the first-hand source, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:22:02.20,0:22:04.21,Default,,0,0,0,,the original source, for that quote. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:22:04.21,0:22:05.51,Default,,0,0,0,,That’s one thing. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:22:05.51,0:22:09.81,Default,,0,0,0,,And secondly, context matters; \Nwe want to quote things properly.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:22:09.81,0:22:14.15,Default,,0,0,0,,When Gandhi and Lord Irwin came together, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:22:14.15,0:22:17.29,Default,,0,0,0,,Gandhi said, ‘When your country \Nand mine come together\N
Dialogue: 0,0:22:17.29,0:22:20.19,Default,,0,0,0,,‘on the teachings of Christ \Nand on the Sermon on the Mount, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:22:20.19,0:22:23.96,Default,,0,0,0,,then we will have solved the problems \Nof our countries and the world.’ \N
Dialogue: 0,0:22:23.96,0:22:25.56,Default,,0,0,0,,So we researched it. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:22:25.56,0:22:28.36,Default,,0,0,0,,No one could confirm \Nthat those two men ever met. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:22:28.36,0:22:30.33,Default,,0,0,0,,So it’s a great quote. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:22:30.33,0:22:32.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, it doesn’t mean \Nthat he didn’t refer to Jesus \N
Dialogue: 0,0:22:32.70,0:22:36.10,Default,,0,0,0,,or even the Sermon on the Mount, \Nbut that particular one, we couldn’t use.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:22:36.10,0:22:38.71,Default,,0,0,0,,So the research work we’re doing, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:22:38.71,0:22:42.21,Default,,0,0,0,,sometimes it takes a lot of time, \Na lot of effort. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:22:42.21,0:22:47.05,Default,,0,0,0,,Sometimes we don’t find \Nwhat we are expecting to find. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:22:47.05,0:22:51.12,Default,,0,0,0,,But it’s very gratifying \Nbecause we’re helping produce \N
Dialogue: 0,0:22:51.12,0:22:54.66,Default,,0,0,0,,accurate information \Nthat our readers can rely on. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:22:54.66,0:22:58.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Reliable information will help us \Nmake good informed decisions.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:22:58.49,0:23:01.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Anyone who reads our journals \Nand who sees our videos \N
Dialogue: 0,0:23:01.20,0:23:05.43,Default,,0,0,0,,can be confident that this \Nwas thoroughly researched. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:23:05.43,0:23:07.90,Default,,0,0,0,,These are facts; this is the truth.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:23:07.90,0:23:10.44,Default,,0,0,0,,So when you consider \Nthe printed publications \N
Dialogue: 0,0:23:10.44,0:23:11.87,Default,,0,0,0,,of Jehovah’s Witnesses \N
Dialogue: 0,0:23:11.87,0:23:14.91,Default,,0,0,0,,or peruse the jw.org website, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:23:14.91,0:23:17.01,Default,,0,0,0,,you can be confident that the material\N
Dialogue: 0,0:23:17.01,0:23:19.71,Default,,0,0,0,,is carefully researched and accurate. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:23:19.71,0:23:21.28,Default,,0,0,0,,Why? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:23:21.28,0:23:23.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Because Jehovah’s Witnesses \N
Dialogue: 0,0:23:23.52,0:23:26.59,Default,,0,0,0,,are a people who love and respect \N
Dialogue: 0,0:23:26.59,0:23:29.00,Default,,0,0,0,,the truth.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:23:31.99,0:23:34.83,Default,,0,0,0,,As Psalm 31:5 expresses, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:23:34.83,0:23:38.93,Default,,0,0,0,,we worship “Jehovah, the God of truth.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:23:38.93,0:23:42.84,Default,,0,0,0,,So it would only make sense \Nthat we try to imitate him \N
Dialogue: 0,0:23:42.84,0:23:45.07,Default,,0,0,0,,to the best of our ability \N
Dialogue: 0,0:23:45.07,0:23:49.58,Default,,0,0,0,,by being truthful \Nin all the materials that we publish. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:23:49.58,0:23:52.41,Default,,0,0,0,,He, no doubt, finds this very pleasing, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:23:52.41,0:23:55.25,Default,,0,0,0,,especially since throughout history, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:23:55.25,0:23:58.69,Default,,0,0,0,,many have tried to twist his teachings.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:23:58.69,0:24:03.43,Default,,0,0,0,,Although the organization makes efforts \Nto publish accurate information, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:24:03.43,0:24:07.73,Default,,0,0,0,,there are many things \Nthat we can do as individuals. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:24:07.73,0:24:12.73,Default,,0,0,0,,This dramatization highlights \Nhow our view of celebrations \N
Dialogue: 0,0:24:12.73,0:24:15.00,Default,,0,0,0,,can be pleasing to Jehovah.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:24:25.85,0:24:26.68,Default,,0,0,0,,Hey, Buddy! \N
Dialogue: 0,0:24:26.68,0:24:28.00,Default,,0,0,0,,How was school?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:24:31.79,0:24:33.82,Default,,0,0,0,,That’s my Dad, Grayson, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:24:33.82,0:24:36.00,Default,,0,0,0,,and my older brother, Dylan.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:24:38.23,0:24:39.06,Default,,0,0,0,,Hey, Bro! \N
Dialogue: 0,0:24:39.06,0:24:40.33,Default,,0,0,0,,We’re going to play ball. \NYou want to come?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:24:40.33,0:24:42.00,Default,,0,0,0,,No thanks.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:24:43.47,0:24:45.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Is he OK?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:24:45.10,0:24:47.60,Default,,0,0,0,,He normally loves to talk about school. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:24:47.60,0:24:50.00,Default,,0,0,0,,He didn’t want to talk about school today.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:24:52.37,0:24:57.00,Default,,0,0,0,,It wasn’t my worst day at school\N—but pretty close. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:24:58.21,0:25:02.42,Default,,0,0,0,,It all started first thing this morning. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:02.42,0:25:06.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Everyone was signing a birthday card \Nfor one of our classmates, Lucas.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:06.49,0:25:08.32,Default,,0,0,0,,Do you want to sign \Nthe birthday card for Lucas?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:08.32,0:25:11.16,Default,,0,0,0,,He just got home from being \Nat the hospital for cancer treatments.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:11.16,0:25:12.13,Default,,0,0,0,,No thanks. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:12.13,0:25:15.06,Default,,0,0,0,,I’m a Jehovah’s Witness, \Nand I don’t celebrate birthdays.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:15.06,0:25:15.93,Default,,0,0,0,,What? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:15.93,0:25:16.73,Default,,0,0,0,,Hum? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:16.73,0:25:17.50,Default,,0,0,0,,That’s rude. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:17.50,0:25:20.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Come on, sign it!\N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:21.57,0:25:24.47,Default,,0,0,0,,You guys, you guys, Aiden—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:24.47,0:25:29.18,Default,,0,0,0,,My teacher said that Lucas \Nmay not come back to school for a long time. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:29.18,0:25:32.00,Default,,0,0,0,,I felt so bad he was sick.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:40.29,0:25:44.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Aiden, Aiden, can you think about it?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:49.70,0:25:53.00,Default,,0,0,0,,The thing is, I did want to sign the card. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:56.14,0:26:00.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Lucas was one of the nicest people \Nin my class. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:00.98,0:26:03.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Maybe I can just sign it. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:04.78,0:26:08.00,Default,,0,0,0,,I mean, it’s not like I’m going\Nto a birthday party.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:13.69,0:26:16.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Hey, little man. \NHow are you doing?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:17.16,0:26:17.99,Default,,0,0,0,,Yeah? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:17.99,0:26:19.89,Default,,0,0,0,,Mom said you had a rough day today.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:19.89,0:26:23.00,Default,,0,0,0,,When Dad came in, \NI told him everything that happened. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:25.17,0:26:29.94,Default,,0,0,0,,I know from the Bible \Nthat it’s wrong to celebrate birthdays. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:29.94,0:26:32.00,Default,,0,0,0,,But is signing the card really a big deal? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:34.54,0:26:37.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Dad said my question was a good one. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:38.21,0:26:40.02,Default,,0,0,0,,Then he showed me a scripture.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:40.02,0:26:41.22,Default,,0,0,0,,Do you want to get your Bible for me? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:41.22,0:26:42.85,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s look in Ephesians 5.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:42.85,0:26:44.92,Default,,0,0,0,,Ephesians 5:10: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:44.92,0:26:50.76,Default,,0,0,0,,“Keep on making sure \Nof what is acceptable to the Lord.”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:50.76,0:26:53.33,Default,,0,0,0,,He said, \N“We all have to keep making sure \N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:53.33,0:26:56.03,Default,,0,0,0,,“of what’s acceptable to Jehovah \N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:56.03,0:27:00.70,Default,,0,0,0,,because Satan is a master at tricking us.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:00.70,0:27:03.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Then he used the example of Aaron.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:08.04,0:27:12.00,Default,,0,0,0,,The Israelites asked Aaron \Nto make them a god.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:16.02,0:27:18.59,Default,,0,0,0,,So Aaron made a golden calf, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:18.59,0:27:22.09,Default,,0,0,0,,thinking that it could represent Jehovah. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:22.09,0:27:24.23,Default,,0,0,0,,He told the people: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:24.23,0:27:28.70,Default,,0,0,0,,“There is a festival to Jehovah tomorrow.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:28.70,0:27:33.03,Default,,0,0,0,,But true worship \Nwas being mixed with false worship, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:33.03,0:27:36.50,Default,,0,0,0,,and Jehovah was not happy. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:36.50,0:27:39.00,Default,,0,0,0,,And many were punished.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:41.41,0:27:44.00,Default,,0,0,0,,That example helped me a lot. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:46.21,0:27:49.45,Default,,0,0,0,,I know birthdays are wrong \Nbecause the Bible teaches \N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:49.45,0:27:52.00,Default,,0,0,0,,that they are not approved by Jehovah. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:53.72,0:27:56.29,Default,,0,0,0,,But we don’t want to be confused like Aaron \N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:56.29,0:27:59.29,Default,,0,0,0,,and try to mix true and false worship.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:59.29,0:28:01.30,Default,,0,0,0,,All right, let’s go talk to Mom.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:01.30,0:28:04.00,Default,,0,0,0,,We want to make Jehovah happy.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:06.43,0:28:10.61,Default,,0,0,0,,So Dad said, \N“It’s always good to ask, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:10.61,0:28:13.27,Default,,0,0,0,,How would Jehovah feel if I did this?”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:13.27,0:28:17.00,Default,,0,0,0,,I still didn’t sign the card, \Nbut I’m going to do something else for Lucas.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:39.37,0:28:41.37,Default,,0,0,0,,Can I go see Lucas?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:41.37,0:28:42.27,Default,,0,0,0,,Yeah. \NGo ahead, Buddy. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:42.27,0:28:43.00,Default,,0,0,0,,He’s right over there.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:53.55,0:28:55.35,Default,,0,0,0,,How have you been feeling?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:55.35,0:28:58.15,Default,,0,0,0,,A little better.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:58.15,0:29:00.86,Default,,0,0,0,,And then I realized something: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:00.86,0:29:03.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Instead of celebrating one day, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:03.59,0:29:05.96,Default,,0,0,0,,I could share with Lucas our hope \N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:05.96,0:29:09.66,Default,,0,0,0,,of living forever \Non a beautiful paradise earth.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:09.66,0:29:13.00,Default,,0,0,0,,So there will be no sickness ever again. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:14.40,0:29:18.00,Default,,0,0,0,,They will build houses and have food.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:20.14,0:29:24.71,Default,,0,0,0,,I enjoyed seeing how we can show \Nlove and concern for others, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:24.71,0:29:27.85,Default,,0,0,0,,even if we do not share their beliefs. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:27.85,0:29:32.52,Default,,0,0,0,,The best way to do so \Nis by simple acts of kindness \N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:32.52,0:29:37.43,Default,,0,0,0,,and by sharing our hope with them, \Njust as Aiden did.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:37.43,0:29:41.73,Default,,0,0,0,,And did you notice \Nhow the good training by Aiden’s parents \N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:41.73,0:29:45.47,Default,,0,0,0,,helped him make decisions \Nthat were pleasing to God? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:45.47,0:29:49.97,Default,,0,0,0,,It made me think of Abilio and Ulla Amorim \Nfrom Portugal. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:49.97,0:29:53.31,Default,,0,0,0,,Both of them endured difficult childhoods, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:53.31,0:29:59.00,Default,,0,0,0,,but they did not allow that to affect \Nhow they raised their own children.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:07.22,0:30:10.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Since I was very young,\NI was religiously inclined\N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:10.59,0:30:15.30,Default,,0,0,0,,and my dream was to get married\Nto a man that worshipped God\N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:15.30,0:30:21.00,Default,,0,0,0,,and that together we would worship God\Nand live a peaceful life. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:21.00,0:30:24.31,Default,,0,0,0,,That didn’t happen with my parents. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:24.31,0:30:29.00,Default,,0,0,0,,We often had a better relationship\Nwith the maid than with my mother.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:32.75,0:30:35.15,Default,,0,0,0,,My father was a very distant person. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:35.15,0:30:39.00,Default,,0,0,0,,He was always very busy\Nwith his work and friends. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:40.29,0:30:45.93,Default,,0,0,0,,We wed in 1971 in Paris, France.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:45.93,0:30:48.76,Default,,0,0,0,,We were baptized in 1974.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:48.76,0:30:53.00,Default,,0,0,0,,I realized I really didn’t know\Nhow to raise children,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:54.14,0:30:56.14,Default,,0,0,0,,and then I started applying some things\N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:56.14,0:30:58.94,Default,,0,0,0,,mentioned in the Bible. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:58.94,0:31:01.11,Default,,0,0,0,,If I wanted to teach them right, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:01.11,0:31:04.25,Default,,0,0,0,,I first had to understand\Nthings better myself \N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:04.25,0:31:09.55,Default,,0,0,0,,so that I could explain them\Nin a way that God would want us to.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:09.55,0:31:13.89,Default,,0,0,0,,In 1976, we moved to Portugal\N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:13.89,0:31:16.00,Default,,0,0,0,,to serve where there was more need. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:18.03,0:31:22.03,Default,,0,0,0,,By then, our oldest son\Nwas four and a half years old, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:22.03,0:31:27.14,Default,,0,0,0,,Maria was three and a half,\Nand Benjamin, one and a half.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:27.14,0:31:32.41,Default,,0,0,0,,I remember when we arrived; \Nwe lived in a rural area.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:32.41,0:31:34.48,Default,,0,0,0,,It was a very small congregation, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:34.48,0:31:37.31,Default,,0,0,0,,so we really had to participate \N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:37.31,0:31:39.05,Default,,0,0,0,,from a very early age.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:39.05,0:31:40.48,Default,,0,0,0,,They wanted to put, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:40.48,0:31:43.92,Default,,0,0,0,,for sure, the spiritual interests\Nfirst in their life, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:43.92,0:31:46.00,Default,,0,0,0,,and they wanted not only to tell us\N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:47.72,0:31:50.00,Default,,0,0,0,,to put the Kingdom interests first\Nbut they wanted to show us\N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:51.33,0:31:52.59,Default,,0,0,0,,how to do it.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:52.59,0:31:56.23,Default,,0,0,0,,And it was not only that we\Nsat down for family study \N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:56.23,0:31:59.10,Default,,0,0,0,,that we talked about Jehovah\Nand spiritual things. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:59.10,0:32:01.67,Default,,0,0,0,,I remember walking back home \N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:01.67,0:32:04.04,Default,,0,0,0,,from meetings\Nand then my parents would help us\N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:04.04,0:32:07.54,Default,,0,0,0,,to look for a star constellation; \N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:07.54,0:32:09.78,Default,,0,0,0,,it started a conversation about Jehovah.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:09.78,0:32:12.88,Default,,0,0,0,,In Deuteronomy chapter 6,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:12.88,0:32:14.88,Default,,0,0,0,,it says that we \Nmust always talk to our children. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:14.88,0:32:16.00,Default,,0,0,0,,But it’s good to talk about God\N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:17.75,0:32:20.02,Default,,0,0,0,,and help them to see God as a real person\N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:20.02,0:32:22.86,Default,,0,0,0,,—a person that is linked\Nto everything around us. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:22.86,0:32:26.19,Default,,0,0,0,,So now I wanted to teach them very much, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:26.19,0:32:27.63,Default,,0,0,0,,and not that things about God \N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:27.63,0:32:30.77,Default,,0,0,0,,were sad or boring,\Nbut were joyful.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:30.77,0:32:33.07,Default,,0,0,0,,Of course, we were imperfect. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:33.07,0:32:36.34,Default,,0,0,0,,Many times I did the wrong things. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:36.34,0:32:39.91,Default,,0,0,0,,I never remember, “You have to do it\Nbecause you have to do it.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:39.91,0:32:42.00,Default,,0,0,0,,They always tried to explain the reasons\N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:43.11,0:32:44.88,Default,,0,0,0,,—Bible reasons.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:44.88,0:32:46.38,Default,,0,0,0,,I was brought up this way. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:46.38,0:32:49.72,Default,,0,0,0,,My parents dictated laws:\N“You have to do this. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:49.72,0:32:52.82,Default,,0,0,0,,You must. \NThis is the way I want it to be.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:52.82,0:32:56.26,Default,,0,0,0,,But I came to understand that God,\Neven in the Bible,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:56.26,0:32:59.93,Default,,0,0,0,,instead of only giving or dictating laws,\Nhe explains them. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:59.93,0:33:03.56,Default,,0,0,0,,He gives so many reasons; \Nhe gives reasons for everything. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:03.56,0:33:08.24,Default,,0,0,0,,By teaching my children,\NI have to say that I have learned a lot too.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:08.24,0:33:11.57,Default,,0,0,0,,We never felt that we must go to meetings; \N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:11.57,0:33:14.84,Default,,0,0,0,,we must go in service\Nbecause you have to do it. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:14.84,0:33:18.18,Default,,0,0,0,,And we were always \Nmotivated to do things.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:18.18,0:33:22.62,Default,,0,0,0,,I remember, for example, \Nwhen he gave me a new Bible,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:22.62,0:33:26.59,Default,,0,0,0,,and he wrote to me in that Bible,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:26.59,0:33:31.59,Default,,0,0,0,,“May this book always be\Nthe motivating force in your life.”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:31.59,0:33:34.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Several times he told me:\N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:34.33,0:33:36.93,Default,,0,0,0,,“Please never,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:36.93,0:33:40.67,Default,,0,0,0,,“never give up in your service. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:40.67,0:33:45.00,Default,,0,0,0,,“Jehovah is your Father,\Nand you have to serve him\N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:48.54,0:33:51.65,Default,,0,0,0,,all your life.”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:51.65,0:33:55.00,Default,,0,0,0,,The Almighty has children\Nthat failed to respond, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:56.65,0:33:59.00,Default,,0,0,0,,much like any other parent. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:34:00.12,0:34:03.62,Default,,0,0,0,,God does not force anyone. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:34:03.62,0:34:07.46,Default,,0,0,0,,He respects our free will very much. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:34:07.46,0:34:11.00,Default,,0,0,0,,So we wanted them\Nto build their own future. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:34:12.70,0:34:16.40,Default,,0,0,0,,I always felt \Nthat my children were not my own,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:34:16.40,0:34:21.18,Default,,0,0,0,,but it was Jehovah\Nwho kindly put them into our hands. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:34:21.18,0:34:25.00,Default,,0,0,0,,He entrusted them to us\Nso that we could care for them. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:34:26.08,0:34:30.00,Default,,0,0,0,,And then when we have done our part,\Nlet them fly.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:34:42.16,0:34:44.50,Default,,0,0,0,,My parents always encouraged us\N
Dialogue: 0,0:34:44.50,0:34:47.14,Default,,0,0,0,,to pursue full-time service,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:34:47.14,0:34:50.00,Default,,0,0,0,,even if that meant\Nmoving far away from home.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:34:52.61,0:34:57.11,Default,,0,0,0,,My husband and I are serving\Nas field missionaries in Klaipeda, Lithuania. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:34:57.11,0:34:59.18,Default,,0,0,0,,I know I will be grateful for all eternity\N
Dialogue: 0,0:34:59.18,0:35:02.65,Default,,0,0,0,,that I used my youth to serve Jehovah,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:35:02.65,0:35:07.46,Default,,0,0,0,,and that I didn’t waste\Nmy years of my young age\N
Dialogue: 0,0:35:07.46,0:35:09.00,Default,,0,0,0,,doing things for this world.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:35:12.29,0:35:15.70,Default,,0,0,0,,My wife and I serve\Nin the Portugal branch office.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:35:15.70,0:35:20.00,Default,,0,0,0,,If Jehovah is happy,\Nif my parents are happy, I’m happy too. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:35:20.00,0:35:22.74,Default,,0,0,0,,I’m really sure\Nthat they like what we’re doing. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:35:22.74,0:35:24.00,Default,,0,0,0,,They are happy with that.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:35:25.84,0:35:29.01,Default,,0,0,0,,We rejoice that our children\Nare giving their best\N
Dialogue: 0,0:35:29.01,0:35:31.35,Default,,0,0,0,,to their Creator and making him happy. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:35:31.35,0:35:34.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Jehovah deserves that.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:35:36.08,0:35:37.99,Default,,0,0,0,,Of course, we miss our children, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:35:37.99,0:35:40.19,Default,,0,0,0,,and we would like to have them around,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:35:40.19,0:35:43.52,Default,,0,0,0,,but we are very happy for them\N
Dialogue: 0,0:35:43.52,0:35:47.00,Default,,0,0,0,,for having the privilege\Nof serving Jehovah the way they are.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:35:50.97,0:35:54.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, the truths found in the Bible \N
Dialogue: 0,0:35:54.20,0:35:58.44,Default,,0,0,0,,can provide practical help \Nin raising a family. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:35:58.44,0:36:01.48,Default,,0,0,0,,But although Jehovah \Nhas given the responsibility \N
Dialogue: 0,0:36:01.48,0:36:04.08,Default,,0,0,0,,of raising children to the parents, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:36:04.08,0:36:08.28,Default,,0,0,0,,other members of the family \Ncan also play an important role \N
Dialogue: 0,0:36:08.28,0:36:11.29,Default,,0,0,0,,in encouraging spiritual progress. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:36:11.29,0:36:15.16,Default,,0,0,0,,These three fleshly sisters \Nlooked after one another \N
Dialogue: 0,0:36:15.16,0:36:19.00,Default,,0,0,0,,while learning about Jehovah.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:36:24.93,0:36:28.70,Default,,0,0,0,,I was the first to start studying the Bible.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:36:28.70,0:36:32.17,Default,,0,0,0,,After that, I started studying too.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:36:32.17,0:36:34.18,Default,,0,0,0,,After watching them for a year, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:36:34.18,0:36:36.18,Default,,0,0,0,,I began studying too.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:36:36.18,0:36:39.21,Default,,0,0,0,,Since our parents had stopped studying,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:36:39.21,0:36:43.65,Default,,0,0,0,,only three of us went to the meetings.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:36:43.65,0:36:46.65,Default,,0,0,0,,We saved our allowance \Nto take the bus to meetings. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:36:46.65,0:36:49.36,Default,,0,0,0,,But sometimes\Nwhen we were short of money—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:36:49.36,0:36:52.16,Default,,0,0,0,,My sisters let me ride the bus, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:36:52.16,0:36:55.86,Default,,0,0,0,,since I’m the youngest,\Nand they would walk.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:36:55.86,0:36:59.00,Default,,0,0,0,,We used to walk\Nan hour and a half each way.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:37:01.54,0:37:05.31,Default,,0,0,0,,Meetings were so important to us \Nthat we never felt it was a burden.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:37:05.31,0:37:08.08,Default,,0,0,0,,May 2007.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:37:08.08,0:37:11.15,Default,,0,0,0,,For me, it was October 2006.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:37:11.15,0:37:16.55,Default,,0,0,0,,I was baptized in October 2005.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:37:16.55,0:37:19.02,Default,,0,0,0,,Three years later,\NI spent a week \N
Dialogue: 0,0:37:19.02,0:37:23.36,Default,,0,0,0,,with a special pioneer \Nwho was serving in the countryside. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:37:23.36,0:37:26.03,Default,,0,0,0,,We prayed together every night \N
Dialogue: 0,0:37:26.03,0:37:29.20,Default,,0,0,0,,and read life stories from The Watchtower. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:37:29.20,0:37:34.60,Default,,0,0,0,,I told Jehovah\Nthat I wanted to be just like her.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:37:34.60,0:37:38.41,Default,,0,0,0,,Although my relatives \Nwere unhappy with my decision, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:37:38.41,0:37:42.28,Default,,0,0,0,,with Jehovah’s help,\NI decided to become a pioneer.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:37:42.28,0:37:46.75,Default,,0,0,0,,I followed her example,\Nand I became a pioneer too.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:37:46.75,0:37:50.12,Default,,0,0,0,,I was working six days a week \Nto support my family, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:37:50.12,0:37:54.46,Default,,0,0,0,,so I prayed to Jehovah \Nfor the opportunity to become a pioneer. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:37:54.46,0:37:57.43,Default,,0,0,0,,After my boss reduced\Nmy work to five days a week,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:37:57.43,0:38:00.00,Default,,0,0,0,,I started pioneering.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:38:01.63,0:38:04.23,Default,,0,0,0,,Pioneer service gives you the opportunity\N
Dialogue: 0,0:38:04.23,0:38:06.47,Default,,0,0,0,,to serve Jehovah more fully.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:38:06.47,0:38:11.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Working closely with Jehovah,\NI really feel part of his family.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:38:12.14,0:38:15.88,Default,,0,0,0,,My relationship with Jehovah\Nhas gotten stronger.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:38:15.88,0:38:19.91,Default,,0,0,0,,When I pray now,\Nit feels like I’m talking to my close friend.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:38:19.91,0:38:22.78,Default,,0,0,0,,It allows you to expand your ministry.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:38:22.78,0:38:27.09,Default,,0,0,0,,I became a special pioneer in June 2013.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:38:27.09,0:38:31.96,Default,,0,0,0,,I’ve served at Bethel since September 2013.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:38:31.96,0:38:36.00,Default,,0,0,0,,In April 2014,\NI was appointed a special pioneer.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:38:37.67,0:38:40.67,Default,,0,0,0,,Now I can serve Jehovah more fully.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:38:40.67,0:38:44.44,Default,,0,0,0,,My appreciation for Jehovah has deepened.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:38:44.44,0:38:49.14,Default,,0,0,0,,Our mother, who had opposed us,\Nbecame a pioneer too.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:38:49.14,0:38:50.81,Default,,0,0,0,,Full-time service is—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:38:50.81,0:38:54.00,Default,,0,0,0,,—really awesome!\N
Dialogue: 0,0:38:55.92,0:38:58.92,Default,,0,0,0,,Whether we are parents or siblings, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:38:58.92,0:39:01.19,Default,,0,0,0,,applying Bible principles \N
Dialogue: 0,0:39:01.19,0:39:04.63,Default,,0,0,0,,helps us to create a strong family bond. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:39:04.63,0:39:07.83,Default,,0,0,0,,It can also help us before we have children, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:39:07.83,0:39:10.60,Default,,0,0,0,,even before we are married. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:39:10.60,0:39:12.77,Default,,0,0,0,,The world tries to tempt us \N
Dialogue: 0,0:39:12.77,0:39:17.34,Default,,0,0,0,,with deceptive lies \Nabout what is important in life. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:39:17.34,0:39:20.71,Default,,0,0,0,,But our own careful research of the Bible \N
Dialogue: 0,0:39:20.71,0:39:25.00,Default,,0,0,0,,can protect and guide us \Nwhen we are planning a wedding.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:39:30.55,0:39:34.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Juliana and I have been friends \Nfor a few years, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:39:35.16,0:39:39.09,Default,,0,0,0,,and we have been getting to know \Neach other better for several months.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:39:39.09,0:39:42.90,Default,,0,0,0,,Things were going really well between us. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:39:42.90,0:39:46.10,Default,,0,0,0,,I must say, when Nick asked me \Nto join some friends \N
Dialogue: 0,0:39:46.10,0:39:48.10,Default,,0,0,0,,for a little get-together at the park, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:39:48.10,0:39:50.30,Default,,0,0,0,,I was getting suspicious \N
Dialogue: 0,0:39:50.30,0:39:53.47,Default,,0,0,0,,when both our families were there. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:39:53.47,0:39:56.00,Default,,0,0,0,,I said, “Yes!”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:39:58.95,0:40:01.00,Default,,0,0,0,,I couldn’t believe she didn’t see it coming. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:40:02.68,0:40:06.00,Default,,0,0,0,,We were both so excited, \Nand word spread fast!\N
Dialogue: 0,0:40:07.69,0:40:11.69,Default,,0,0,0,,At the meeting the next day, \Neveryone was congratulating us\N
Dialogue: 0,0:40:11.69,0:40:14.03,Default,,0,0,0,,—my friend Natalie especially. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:40:14.03,0:40:17.93,Default,,0,0,0,,She was full of ideas.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:40:17.93,0:40:20.00,Default,,0,0,0,,I couldn’t wait to start making plans.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:40:22.37,0:40:25.71,Default,,0,0,0,,I never realized \Nhow much goes into a wedding. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:40:25.71,0:40:28.78,Default,,0,0,0,,And everyone had \Ntheir own ideas of what we needed\N
Dialogue: 0,0:40:28.78,0:40:30.78,Default,,0,0,0,,—even Dad! \N
Dialogue: 0,0:40:30.78,0:40:33.28,Default,,0,0,0,,We had to think about who we would invite, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:40:33.28,0:40:36.02,Default,,0,0,0,,pick out flowers, decorations, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:40:36.02,0:40:40.05,Default,,0,0,0,,a suit for Nick and, of course, a dress! \N
Dialogue: 0,0:40:40.05,0:40:42.06,Default,,0,0,0,,This was going to be \N
Dialogue: 0,0:40:42.06,0:40:46.00,Default,,0,0,0,,so much fun\N—or so I thought.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:40:47.03,0:40:51.67,Default,,0,0,0,,I soon found out there’s \Na whole wedding-related industry out there. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:40:51.67,0:40:56.34,Default,,0,0,0,,They were trying to be helpful but, \Nat the same time, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:40:56.34,0:40:58.67,Default,,0,0,0,,this is how they make money. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:40:58.67,0:41:02.68,Default,,0,0,0,,It seemed like nothing they had was modest. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:41:02.68,0:41:07.18,Default,,0,0,0,,And the cost for something \NI would only wear for one day\N
Dialogue: 0,0:41:07.18,0:41:09.52,Default,,0,0,0,,—I couldn’t afford that! \N
Dialogue: 0,0:41:09.52,0:41:12.05,Default,,0,0,0,,Everyone was so happy for me, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:41:12.05,0:41:16.00,Default,,0,0,0,,but inside I was really starting \Nto feel the pressure.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:41:17.99,0:41:20.19,Default,,0,0,0,,When we met back at Juliana’s home, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:41:20.19,0:41:22.73,Default,,0,0,0,,I was pretty confused. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:41:22.73,0:41:25.43,Default,,0,0,0,,She had been so happy a few days ago, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:41:25.43,0:41:28.07,Default,,0,0,0,,but now she was so stressed out. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:41:28.07,0:41:31.71,Default,,0,0,0,,It was like nobody \Nwas listening to what we wanted. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:41:31.71,0:41:33.71,Default,,0,0,0,,But to be honest, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:41:33.71,0:41:36.00,Default,,0,0,0,,I’m not sure we knew\Nwhat we wanted either. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:41:37.61,0:41:41.02,Default,,0,0,0,,I thought it would be good \Nif maybe we could just take some time \N
Dialogue: 0,0:41:41.02,0:41:45.00,Default,,0,0,0,,and think about what a Christian wedding \Nshould really be like.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:41:46.92,0:41:49.89,Default,,0,0,0,,We had a meeting with Brother Grey \Nand Brother Sharp the next day \N
Dialogue: 0,0:41:49.89,0:41:52.46,Default,,0,0,0,,to discuss using the Kingdom Hall \Nfor our wedding. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:41:52.46,0:41:54.36,Default,,0,0,0,,They gave us some helpful reminders, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:41:54.36,0:41:57.06,Default,,0,0,0,,and I’m so glad they did. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:41:57.06,0:41:59.97,Default,,0,0,0,,First Corinthians 10:31 says: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:41:59.97,0:42:04.31,Default,,0,0,0,,“Whether you are eating \Nor drinking or doing anything else, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:42:04.31,0:42:07.64,Default,,0,0,0,,do all things for God’s glory.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:42:07.64,0:42:11.81,Default,,0,0,0,,Brother Sharp helped us to see \Nthat a wedding is a spiritual occasion, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:42:11.81,0:42:13.91,Default,,0,0,0,,and we need to keep \NJehovah’s standards in mind \N
Dialogue: 0,0:42:13.91,0:42:17.00,Default,,0,0,0,,when we plan for what we will \Nor won’t choose to include.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:42:18.82,0:42:23.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Brother Grey showed us 1 John 2:15, 16: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:42:23.42,0:42:27.63,Default,,0,0,0,,“Do not love either the world\Nor the things in the world.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:42:27.63,0:42:30.40,Default,,0,0,0,,“. . . Because everything in the world\N
Dialogue: 0,0:42:30.40,0:42:34.13,Default,,0,0,0,,“—the desire of the flesh\Nand the desire of the eyes\N
Dialogue: 0,0:42:34.13,0:42:36.94,Default,,0,0,0,,“and the showy display\Nof one’s means of life—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:42:36.94,0:42:39.74,Default,,0,0,0,,. . . originates with the world.”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:42:39.74,0:42:43.44,Default,,0,0,0,,He reminded us that what\Nthe world views as normal\N
Dialogue: 0,0:42:43.44,0:42:46.51,Default,,0,0,0,,is far different from Christian standards \N
Dialogue: 0,0:42:46.51,0:42:49.42,Default,,0,0,0,,and that we can be a good example \N
Dialogue: 0,0:42:49.42,0:42:52.85,Default,,0,0,0,,by making sure our choices please Jehovah.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:42:52.85,0:42:57.36,Default,,0,0,0,,They even gave us a few articles \Nabout wedding arrangements to review. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:42:57.36,0:43:01.00,Default,,0,0,0,,They wanted to make sure we would have \Na happy occasion with nothing to regret. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:43:02.93,0:43:06.43,Default,,0,0,0,,I asked Brother Sharp \Nif he would be our director of the feast \N
Dialogue: 0,0:43:06.43,0:43:08.44,Default,,0,0,0,,to help keep things coordinated, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:43:08.44,0:43:12.00,Default,,0,0,0,,and he suggested that we talk \Nabout it over dinner that night.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:43:13.54,0:43:17.85,Default,,0,0,0,,On the way there, \Nwe passed by a photography studio. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:43:17.85,0:43:21.72,Default,,0,0,0,,I couldn’t believe how lavish \Nand showy some weddings are. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:43:21.72,0:43:24.52,Default,,0,0,0,,It looked more like an excuse to party \N
Dialogue: 0,0:43:24.52,0:43:28.22,Default,,0,0,0,,instead of something \Nthat’s supposed to honor God.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:43:28.22,0:43:30.22,Default,,0,0,0,,It reminded me of the book of Galatians: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:43:30.22,0:43:32.69,Default,,0,0,0,,“Now the works of the flesh are . . .\N
Dialogue: 0,0:43:32.69,0:43:36.46,Default,,0,0,0,,drunkenness, wild parties, \Nand things like these.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:43:36.46,0:43:40.03,Default,,0,0,0,,We didn’t want to do anything like that. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:43:40.03,0:43:42.90,Default,,0,0,0,,We each took the time\Nto prayerfully consider\N
Dialogue: 0,0:43:42.90,0:43:45.97,Default,,0,0,0,,the material the brothers gave us.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:43:45.97,0:43:49.51,Default,,0,0,0,,We saw that Scriptural principles \Ncan even help us plan a wedding \N
Dialogue: 0,0:43:49.51,0:43:53.05,Default,,0,0,0,,that’s affordable, \Nenjoyable for everyone, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:43:53.05,0:43:56.00,Default,,0,0,0,,and a day that honors Jehovah. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:43:57.69,0:44:00.55,Default,,0,0,0,,It looked like we needed \Nto make some adjustments. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:44:00.55,0:44:03.89,Default,,0,0,0,,We couldn’t include \Neverything we originally thought\N
Dialogue: 0,0:44:03.89,0:44:06.00,Default,,0,0,0,,—some things were just too expensive.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:44:07.39,0:44:09.60,Default,,0,0,0,,And we wanted to make sure \Nthat none of our choices \N
Dialogue: 0,0:44:09.60,0:44:12.00,Default,,0,0,0,,reflected the spirit of the world.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:44:14.70,0:44:17.54,Default,,0,0,0,,So we decided to start over \N
Dialogue: 0,0:44:17.54,0:44:20.77,Default,,0,0,0,,and make sure we\Nwere doing things Jehovah’s way.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:44:20.77,0:44:24.95,Default,,0,0,0,,First Timothy 2:9 says that a Christian \N
Dialogue: 0,0:44:24.95,0:44:29.58,Default,,0,0,0,,“should adorn themselves \Nin appropriate [or “respectable”] dress, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:44:29.58,0:44:32.29,Default,,0,0,0,,with modesty and soundness of mind.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:44:32.29,0:44:34.29,Default,,0,0,0,,It took some work, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:44:34.29,0:44:38.19,Default,,0,0,0,,but we were able \Nto find something affordable, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:44:38.19,0:44:40.93,Default,,0,0,0,,appropriate, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:44:40.93,0:44:43.00,Default,,0,0,0,,and beautiful.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:44:45.80,0:44:48.57,Default,,0,0,0,,I was able to find a nice suit\N
Dialogue: 0,0:44:48.57,0:44:51.81,Default,,0,0,0,,—something I could even wear later. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:44:51.81,0:44:54.21,Default,,0,0,0,,And of course, the girls came by \N
Dialogue: 0,0:44:54.21,0:44:57.00,Default,,0,0,0,,to make sure that everything matched.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:44:58.15,0:45:00.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Time went by so fast. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:45:01.72,0:45:03.95,Default,,0,0,0,,I called Brother Sharp \Nso he could help us follow through \N
Dialogue: 0,0:45:03.95,0:45:06.00,Default,,0,0,0,,on the day of the wedding.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:45:08.39,0:45:11.23,Default,,0,0,0,,Before we knew it, \Nwe were sending out invitations \N
Dialogue: 0,0:45:11.23,0:45:14.00,Default,,0,0,0,,and finalizing all the details.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:45:17.00,0:45:20.23,Default,,0,0,0,,When my dad walked me \Ndown the aisle that day, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:45:20.23,0:45:22.34,Default,,0,0,0,,I was so excited.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:45:22.34,0:45:25.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Juliana was so beautiful! \N
Dialogue: 0,0:45:26.97,0:45:31.00,Default,,0,0,0,,And the ceremony was just perfect. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:45:35.12,0:45:39.00,Default,,0,0,0,,After all that planning we did, \Nwe were sure to make it legal.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:45:41.19,0:45:43.62,Default,,0,0,0,,When looking back at our photos, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:45:43.62,0:45:46.59,Default,,0,0,0,,it brings back so many good memories.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:45:46.59,0:45:49.00,Default,,0,0,0,,I was so happy \Nwith how nice everything turned out. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:45:51.13,0:45:53.70,Default,,0,0,0,,And when we saw \Nwhat a great job our friends had done \N
Dialogue: 0,0:45:53.70,0:45:57.70,Default,,0,0,0,,decorating the reception, \NI couldn’t believe my eyes.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:45:57.70,0:46:00.51,Default,,0,0,0,,It was perfect\N—simple, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:46:00.51,0:46:03.18,Default,,0,0,0,,dignified. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:46:03.18,0:46:07.82,Default,,0,0,0,,Our friends all told us that it was \None of the nicest weddings they’ve been to. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:46:07.82,0:46:10.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Everything that day\Nwas just what we wanted. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:46:10.95,0:46:13.00,Default,,0,0,0,,It even stayed on budget.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:46:14.35,0:46:17.99,Default,,0,0,0,,And most importantly, \Nwe got our marriage off to a good start \N
Dialogue: 0,0:46:17.99,0:46:20.00,Default,,0,0,0,,with Jehovah’s help.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:46:21.36,0:46:23.73,Default,,0,0,0,,I’m so happy we found each other.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:46:23.73,0:46:26.00,Default,,0,0,0,,I’m so happy I found you too, Love. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:46:27.30,0:46:31.00,Default,,0,0,0,,And I know we’ll stay happy \Nif we keep Jehovah first.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:46:35.18,0:46:38.75,Default,,0,0,0,,The couple’s ability to reason \Non Scriptural principles \N
Dialogue: 0,0:46:38.75,0:46:42.12,Default,,0,0,0,,helped them to make \Nthe right decisions. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:46:42.12,0:46:46.85,Default,,0,0,0,,Good reasoning ability \Nis an essential quality of a true Christian. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:46:46.85,0:46:51.69,Default,,0,0,0,,But what does it really mean \Nto reason on matters? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:46:51.69,0:46:56.00,Default,,0,0,0,,This morning worship program \Nby Gary Breaux will show us.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:46:57.11,0:47:01.20,Default,,0,0,0,,If you’d open your Bibles to Romans 12:1, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:47:01.20,0:47:04.10,Default,,0,0,0,,we’ll note that the apostle Paul, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:47:04.10,0:47:06.34,Default,,0,0,0,,as has been commented on, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:47:06.34,0:47:10.71,Default,,0,0,0,,talks about reasoning on matters. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:47:10.71,0:47:14.52,Default,,0,0,0,,That’s Romans 12:1, it says: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:47:14.52,0:47:17.99,Default,,0,0,0,,“Therefore, I appeal to you \Nby the compassions of God, brothers, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:47:17.99,0:47:21.19,Default,,0,0,0,,“to present your bodies \Nas a living sacrifice, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:47:21.19,0:47:23.82,Default,,0,0,0,,“holy and acceptable to God, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:47:23.82,0:47:28.00,Default,,0,0,0,,a sacred service \Nwith your power of reason.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:47:29.16,0:47:34.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Ah, so Paul says reasoning has power to it. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:47:34.84,0:47:39.71,Default,,0,0,0,,A synonym for power is influence. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:47:39.71,0:47:42.54,Default,,0,0,0,,And so if you reason something out, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:47:42.54,0:47:46.88,Default,,0,0,0,,you’ll be influenced to make \Nthe proper decision, basically.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:47:46.88,0:47:50.55,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, he also introduced \Nsomething else in our text today. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:47:50.55,0:47:51.35,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s go there. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:47:51.35,0:47:54.25,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s 2 Thessalonians chapter 2,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:47:54.25,0:47:58.00,Default,,0,0,0,,and we’ll read verses 1 and 2:\N
Dialogue: 0,0:48:00.66,0:48:02.66,Default,,0,0,0,,“However, brothers, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:48:02.66,0:48:05.40,Default,,0,0,0,,“concerning the presence\Nof our Lord Jesus Christ\N
Dialogue: 0,0:48:05.40,0:48:07.63,Default,,0,0,0,,“and our being gathered together to him,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:48:07.63,0:48:12.64,Default,,0,0,0,,“we ask you not to be\Nquickly shaken from your reason\N
Dialogue: 0,0:48:12.64,0:48:17.68,Default,,0,0,0,,“nor to be alarmed\Neither by an inspired statement\N
Dialogue: 0,0:48:17.68,0:48:22.68,Default,,0,0,0,,“or by a spoken message\Nor by a letter appearing to be from us,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:48:22.68,0:48:27.99,Default,,0,0,0,,to the effect\Nthat the day of Jehovah is here.”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:48:27.99,0:48:31.12,Default,,0,0,0,,So he introduces this aspect\N
Dialogue: 0,0:48:31.12,0:48:34.80,Default,,0,0,0,,of being quickly shaken\N
Dialogue: 0,0:48:34.80,0:48:38.20,Default,,0,0,0,,once you come to a conclusion on a matter \N
Dialogue: 0,0:48:38.20,0:48:40.57,Default,,0,0,0,,after reasoning it out.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:48:40.57,0:48:43.34,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, he says don’t be quickly shaken \N
Dialogue: 0,0:48:43.34,0:48:46.31,Default,,0,0,0,,once you come to a conclusion of the matter \N
Dialogue: 0,0:48:46.31,0:48:49.61,Default,,0,0,0,,as a result of reasoning the matter out. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:48:49.61,0:48:53.51,Default,,0,0,0,,And that’s what he was telling \Nthe Thessalonica congregation here. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:48:53.51,0:48:56.88,Default,,0,0,0,,In the first letter, \Nhe had talked about and warned them \N
Dialogue: 0,0:48:56.88,0:49:01.66,Default,,0,0,0,,that Jehovah’s day was imminent \Nand that it was coming, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:49:01.66,0:49:04.86,Default,,0,0,0,,and as a result, \Nsome in the congregation went beyond that, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:49:04.86,0:49:06.89,Default,,0,0,0,,saying that it was here. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:49:06.89,0:49:08.90,Default,,0,0,0,,In fact, as verse 2 says, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:49:08.90,0:49:13.83,Default,,0,0,0,,there apparently was even a letter \Nthat appeared to be from Paul \N
Dialogue: 0,0:49:13.83,0:49:17.60,Default,,0,0,0,,and saying that it’s not that it’s coming\N
Dialogue: 0,0:49:17.60,0:49:20.41,Default,,0,0,0,,—Jehovah’s day is here. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:49:20.41,0:49:24.21,Default,,0,0,0,,And so some got sidetracked \N
Dialogue: 0,0:49:24.21,0:49:27.81,Default,,0,0,0,,as a result of not thinking it through, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:49:27.81,0:49:29.98,Default,,0,0,0,,and their faith was shaken, apparently. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:49:29.98,0:49:32.65,Default,,0,0,0,,And then as you continue, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:49:32.65,0:49:36.46,Default,,0,0,0,,Paul then helped them \Nto reason further that no, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:49:36.46,0:49:41.00,Default,,0,0,0,,there are other things \Nthat have to happen before Jehovah’s day.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:49:42.16,0:49:44.50,Default,,0,0,0,,So we’d like to talk about this matter \N
Dialogue: 0,0:49:44.50,0:49:48.00,Default,,0,0,0,,of quickly being shaken\N—that is our faith. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:49:49.07,0:49:54.07,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s important because we spend years\N
Dialogue: 0,0:49:54.07,0:49:56.64,Default,,0,0,0,,developing a relationship with Jehovah God\N
Dialogue: 0,0:49:56.64,0:49:59.01,Default,,0,0,0,,and developing a solid faith, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:49:59.01,0:50:01.55,Default,,0,0,0,,and just this idea that Paul introduces \N
Dialogue: 0,0:50:01.55,0:50:04.99,Default,,0,0,0,,that one’s faith can be quickly shaken \N
Dialogue: 0,0:50:04.99,0:50:07.00,Default,,0,0,0,,is a rather disconcerting thought. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:50:09.36,0:50:11.46,Default,,0,0,0,,It can happen to any of us, really. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:50:11.46,0:50:13.93,Default,,0,0,0,,I just think about Judas Iscariot, right? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:50:13.93,0:50:18.40,Default,,0,0,0,,John 6:64 says \Nthat from the beginning Jesus knew \N
Dialogue: 0,0:50:18.40,0:50:21.40,Default,,0,0,0,,who was the one who would betray him\N—from the beginning. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:50:21.40,0:50:23.40,Default,,0,0,0,,From the beginning of what? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:50:23.40,0:50:24.54,Default,,0,0,0,,The Insight book says: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:50:24.54,0:50:27.84,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘From the beginning’ \Nof when Judas started to go bad, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:50:27.84,0:50:32.01,Default,,0,0,0,,started to give in to imperfection \Nand sinful inclinations.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:50:32.01,0:50:34.45,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, how long did that process take? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:50:34.45,0:50:38.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, it was less than a year \Nfrom the time he was appointed as an apostle. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:50:38.52,0:50:43.19,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, we know his appointment \Nwas no mistake. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:50:43.19,0:50:46.39,Default,,0,0,0,,So within that short period of time, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:50:46.39,0:50:51.40,Default,,0,0,0,,this man went from an apostle \Nto an apostate. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:50:51.40,0:50:55.60,Default,,0,0,0,,That’s why it’s such good counsel \Nthat Paul gave \N
Dialogue: 0,0:50:55.60,0:50:59.14,Default,,0,0,0,,for us not to be quickly shaken \N
Dialogue: 0,0:50:59.14,0:51:05.05,Default,,0,0,0,,from matters that we have established\Nas a result of good reasoning.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:51:05.05,0:51:09.25,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, there are times \Nthat we’re more susceptible \N
Dialogue: 0,0:51:09.25,0:51:13.69,Default,,0,0,0,,to our faith\Nbeing quickly shaken than others. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:51:13.69,0:51:16.86,Default,,0,0,0,,And I’d like to talk \Nabout that for just a moment. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:51:16.86,0:51:19.86,Default,,0,0,0,,What could some of those times be? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:51:19.86,0:51:24.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, it could be \Nwhen we’re going through stress, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:51:24.10,0:51:28.47,Default,,0,0,0,,depression, or anxiety. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:51:28.47,0:51:32.97,Default,,0,0,0,,The March 1, 2010, Watchtower, \Nmakes this comment: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:51:32.97,0:51:35.44,Default,,0,0,0,,“Judgment may be clouded \N
Dialogue: 0,0:51:35.44,0:51:39.78,Default,,0,0,0,,when one is under great emotional stress.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:51:39.78,0:51:42.45,Default,,0,0,0,,Now let me give you an example\N
Dialogue: 0,0:51:42.45,0:51:45.49,Default,,0,0,0,,—hypothetical, but here’s an example—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:51:45.49,0:51:49.52,Default,,0,0,0,,a brother has a deep relationship \Nwith his parents; \N
Dialogue: 0,0:51:49.52,0:51:52.53,Default,,0,0,0,,his mother suddenly dies. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:51:52.53,0:51:56.66,Default,,0,0,0,,This is a great emotional blow to him; \N
Dialogue: 0,0:51:56.66,0:52:01.54,Default,,0,0,0,,he slips into a mild depression, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:52:01.54,0:52:05.07,Default,,0,0,0,,and as a result, his personal study \N
Dialogue: 0,0:52:05.07,0:52:09.68,Default,,0,0,0,,and his spiritual activities slow down. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:52:09.68,0:52:14.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Then a short time later, \Na sibling is disfellowshipped. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:52:15.68,0:52:19.85,Default,,0,0,0,,This crushes him; he can’t sleep. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:52:19.85,0:52:23.00,Default,,0,0,0,,He wakes up; he gets to the computer; \N
Dialogue: 0,0:52:24.49,0:52:26.89,Default,,0,0,0,,he turns it on, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:52:26.89,0:52:30.00,Default,,0,0,0,,and he slips into watching\Nsomething inappropriate.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:52:31.67,0:52:33.67,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, what’s just happened? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:52:33.67,0:52:37.14,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, his good reasoning ability was shaken. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:52:37.14,0:52:41.81,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s of note \Nthat the November 15, 1992, Watchtower, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:52:41.81,0:52:43.81,Default,,0,0,0,,puts it this way: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:52:43.81,0:52:47.01,Default,,0,0,0,,“Severe and prolonged mental depression \N
Dialogue: 0,0:52:47.01,0:52:49.25,Default,,0,0,0,,“may have worn away \N
Dialogue: 0,0:52:49.25,0:52:53.59,Default,,0,0,0,,“some of the person’s normally \Nstrong emotional fiber \N
Dialogue: 0,0:52:53.59,0:52:57.99,Default,,0,0,0,,or may have made it extremely difficult \Nto make wise decisions.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:52:57.99,0:53:00.66,Default,,0,0,0,,So, what could the brother have done? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:53:00.66,0:53:04.93,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, when he first recognized \Nthis mild depression \N
Dialogue: 0,0:53:04.93,0:53:08.57,Default,,0,0,0,,or slipping from the spiritual activities, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:53:08.57,0:53:13.24,Default,,0,0,0,,it would have been good for him to get\Nsomeone to help him identify the cause.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:53:13.24,0:53:16.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, what is another circumstance \N
Dialogue: 0,0:53:16.38,0:53:21.18,Default,,0,0,0,,that could quickly shake our faith\N
Dialogue: 0,0:53:21.18,0:53:23.98,Default,,0,0,0,,if we’re not on guard?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:53:23.98,0:53:26.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, it has to do with the apostates. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:53:28.39,0:53:33.39,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, there is something \Nthat the apostates are talking about \N
Dialogue: 0,0:53:33.39,0:53:35.83,Default,,0,0,0,,and trying to put forward. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:53:35.83,0:53:40.60,Default,,0,0,0,,The media has picked it up; \Nothers have also picked it up. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:53:40.60,0:53:42.90,Default,,0,0,0,,And that is our Scriptural position \N
Dialogue: 0,0:53:42.90,0:53:45.57,Default,,0,0,0,,of having a two-witnesses requirement \N
Dialogue: 0,0:53:45.57,0:53:48.61,Default,,0,0,0,,for judicial action \Nif there is no confession. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:53:48.61,0:53:51.44,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, if you open your Bibles \Nto Deuteronomy 19:15, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:53:51.44,0:53:54.51,Default,,0,0,0,,our good reasoning is pretty solid on this. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:53:54.51,0:53:57.52,Default,,0,0,0,,At Deuteronomy 19:15,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:53:57.52,0:54:02.19,Default,,0,0,0,,the scripture is very, very clear. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:54:02.19,0:54:06.53,Default,,0,0,0,,It says: \N“No single witness may convict another \N
Dialogue: 0,0:54:06.53,0:54:09.83,Default,,0,0,0,,“for any error or any sin that he may commit. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:54:09.83,0:54:12.00,Default,,0,0,0,,“On the testimony of two witnesses \N
Dialogue: 0,0:54:12.00,0:54:14.07,Default,,0,0,0,,“or on the testimony of three witnesses \N
Dialogue: 0,0:54:14.07,0:54:16.07,Default,,0,0,0,,the matter should be established.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:54:16.07,0:54:17.74,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s very clear, isn’t it? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:54:17.74,0:54:22.64,Default,,0,0,0,,You cannot establish \Na judicial committee based on one witness. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:54:22.64,0:54:25.45,Default,,0,0,0,,But now, listen, \Nhere’s what they say: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:54:25.45,0:54:27.71,Default,,0,0,0,,“Well now, look, \Nthe Old Testament \N
Dialogue: 0,0:54:27.71,0:54:31.00,Default,,0,0,0,,“also says that adulteresses \Nshould be stoned.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:54:32.82,0:54:35.46,Default,,0,0,0,,“Now, since you’re not doing that, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:54:35.46,0:54:40.00,Default,,0,0,0,,why do you stick \Nto this two-witness rule?” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:54:41.26,0:54:45.50,Default,,0,0,0,,You see, if you’re not careful, \Nthat can do some tricks on your mind \N
Dialogue: 0,0:54:45.50,0:54:48.13,Default,,0,0,0,,because you have to think it through. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:54:48.13,0:54:50.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, how might we do that? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:54:50.20,0:54:53.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, we go to Matthew 18:16\N
Dialogue: 0,0:54:53.04,0:54:56.31,Default,,0,0,0,,because obviously Christ Jesus\N
Dialogue: 0,0:54:56.31,0:54:58.65,Default,,0,0,0,,established the Christian arrangement,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:54:58.65,0:55:00.65,Default,,0,0,0,,and notice what he said.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:55:00.65,0:55:04.28,Default,,0,0,0,,Matthew 18:16, he says: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:55:04.28,0:55:08.05,Default,,0,0,0,,“But if he does not listen,\Ntake along with you one or two more,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:55:08.05,0:55:12.33,Default,,0,0,0,,“so that on the testimony\Nof two or three witnesses\N
Dialogue: 0,0:55:12.33,0:55:15.50,Default,,0,0,0,,every matter may be established.”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:55:15.50,0:55:20.53,Default,,0,0,0,,So Christ Jesus establishes the fact\Nthat there has to be two witnesses.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:55:20.53,0:55:23.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, it doesn’t mean \Nthat if there is only one witness \N
Dialogue: 0,0:55:23.84,0:55:25.84,Default,,0,0,0,,that there are no consequences. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:55:25.84,0:55:28.14,Default,,0,0,0,,There might be, \Ndepending upon the situation, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:55:28.14,0:55:31.41,Default,,0,0,0,,but the Scriptures are very clear. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:55:31.41,0:55:34.65,Default,,0,0,0,,Before a judicial committee can be convened, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:55:34.65,0:55:38.69,Default,,0,0,0,,there has to be a confession \Nor two witnesses, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:55:38.69,0:55:41.72,Default,,0,0,0,,so we will never change \N
Dialogue: 0,0:55:41.72,0:55:45.13,Default,,0,0,0,,our Scriptural position on that subject.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:55:45.13,0:55:50.03,Default,,0,0,0,,Jehovah has given us the ability \Nto reason things out, to think it through. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:55:50.03,0:55:52.03,Default,,0,0,0,,So let’s do our part \N
Dialogue: 0,0:55:52.03,0:55:55.87,Default,,0,0,0,,and not allow our faith\Nto be quickly shaken.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:55:55.87,0:55:59.27,Default,,0,0,0,,Then we can have \Nthe confidence that Paul spoke of \N
Dialogue: 0,0:55:59.27,0:56:02.04,Default,,0,0,0,,at 2 Thessalonians 3:5 when he said: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:56:02.04,0:56:05.71,Default,,0,0,0,,“May the Lord continue to guide\Nyour hearts successfully\N
Dialogue: 0,0:56:05.71,0:56:09.00,Default,,0,0,0,,to the love of God\Nand to the endurance for the Christ.”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:56:10.78,0:56:13.79,Default,,0,0,0,,Even when difficult circumstances arise, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:56:13.79,0:56:15.86,Default,,0,0,0,,such as judicial matters, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:56:15.86,0:56:19.96,Default,,0,0,0,,we cling to our accurate understanding \Nof the Bible. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:56:19.96,0:56:24.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, Jehovah is the God of truth. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:56:24.70,0:56:27.57,Default,,0,0,0,,And our desire for accurate knowledge \N
Dialogue: 0,0:56:27.57,0:56:31.00,Default,,0,0,0,,motivates us to draw \Never closer to Jehovah \N
Dialogue: 0,0:56:31.00,0:56:34.77,Default,,0,0,0,,and to learn more \Nabout his perfect qualities. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:56:34.77,0:56:38.31,Default,,0,0,0,,Just think of everything \Nwe can learn about him \N
Dialogue: 0,0:56:38.31,0:56:42.65,Default,,0,0,0,,when we take the time \Nto study his works of creation. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:56:42.65,0:56:46.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Psalm 104:24 reads: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:56:46.42,0:56:50.02,Default,,0,0,0,,“How many your works are, O Jehovah! \N
Dialogue: 0,0:56:50.02,0:56:52.69,Default,,0,0,0,,“You have made all of them in wisdom. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:56:52.69,0:56:56.00,Default,,0,0,0,,The earth is full of what you have made.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:56:57.10,0:57:00.63,Default,,0,0,0,,In harmony with that, \Nour music video for this month \N
Dialogue: 0,0:57:00.63,0:57:05.74,Default,,0,0,0,,is entitled Inspired by Your Wonders.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:57:05.74,0:57:10.00,Default,,0,0,0,,I hear the birds singing out\Nto the sunrise.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:57:13.15,0:57:20.00,Default,,0,0,0,,I see the stars fading away\Nin the morning light.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:57:24.92,0:57:30.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Golden sun shines on down\Nthrough the treetops,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:57:32.13,0:57:41.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Where there is a summer breeze\Nthat whispers so soft.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:57:41.57,0:57:45.98,Default,,0,0,0,,And I sing,\N“O Jah, Jehovah my God,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:57:45.98,0:57:50.98,Default,,0,0,0,,The work of your hands\Nfills us with awe.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:57:50.98,0:57:59.00,Default,,0,0,0,,I stare at the stars,\NWondering how you care who we are.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:58:01.19,0:58:08.00,Default,,0,0,0,,I see your wonders,\Nand I sing to you.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:58:11.27,0:58:19.85,Default,,0,0,0,,I see your wonders,\Nand I sing to you.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:58:19.85,0:58:22.00,Default,,0,0,0,,I sing to you.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:58:27.22,0:58:33.00,Default,,0,0,0,,These wondrous, moving,\Nbreathing creations—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:58:34.33,0:58:43.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh, in the night, in the day—\Ncan you hear what they say?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:58:46.31,0:58:52.00,Default,,0,0,0,,From mountaintops\Nto the bottoms of oceans,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:58:53.75,0:59:03.26,Default,,0,0,0,,Let ev’ry living thing\Nsing out to your praise.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:59:03.26,0:59:07.43,Default,,0,0,0,,And I sing,\N“O Jah, Jehovah my God,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:59:07.43,0:59:12.33,Default,,0,0,0,,The work of your hands\Nfills us with awe.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:59:12.33,0:59:21.91,Default,,0,0,0,,I stare at the stars,\NWondering how you care who we are.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:59:21.91,0:59:31.00,Default,,0,0,0,,I see your wonders,\Nand I sing to you.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:59:32.02,0:59:41.79,Default,,0,0,0,,I see your wonders, \Nand I sing to you.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:59:41.79,0:59:44.00,Default,,0,0,0,,I sing to you.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:59:45.77,0:59:51.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Looking past what we \Ncan see with our eyes,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:59:54.31,1:00:03.00,Default,,0,0,0,,We will come to know more \Nabout the One who gave us life.\N
Dialogue: 0,1:00:05.25,1:00:10.06,Default,,0,0,0,,And I sing,\N“O Jah, Jehovah my God,\N
Dialogue: 0,1:00:10.06,1:00:14.99,Default,,0,0,0,,The work of your hands\Nfills us with awe.” \N
Dialogue: 0,1:00:14.99,1:00:23.00,Default,,0,0,0,,I stare at the stars,\NWondering how you care who we are.\N
Dialogue: 0,1:00:25.07,1:00:33.91,Default,,0,0,0,,I see your wonders,\Nand I sing to you.\N
Dialogue: 0,1:00:33.91,1:00:42.00,Default,,0,0,0,,I see your wonders,\Nand I sing to you.\N
Dialogue: 0,1:00:43.49,1:00:52.00,Default,,0,0,0,,I see your wonders,\Nand I—I sing to you.\N
Dialogue: 0,1:00:54.00,1:01:01.00,Default,,0,0,0,,I see your wonders,\Nand I—I sing to you.\N
Dialogue: 0,1:01:03.34,1:01:11.00,Default,,0,0,0,,I see your wonders,\Nand I—I sing to you.\N
Dialogue: 0,1:01:12.69,1:01:16.00,Default,,0,0,0,,I sing to you.\N
Dialogue: 0,1:01:17.99,1:01:21.69,Default,,0,0,0,,When we take time to reflect \Non the beauties of creation, \N
Dialogue: 0,1:01:21.69,1:01:25.57,Default,,0,0,0,,it becomes clear \Nthat there is a higher intelligence \N
Dialogue: 0,1:01:25.57,1:01:28.10,Default,,0,0,0,,who made all these things. \N
Dialogue: 0,1:01:28.10,1:01:30.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, David, it’s hard to imagine \N
Dialogue: 0,1:01:30.50,1:01:34.07,Default,,0,0,0,,that we’ve already come to the end \Nof another monthly broadcast.\N
Dialogue: 0,1:01:34.07,1:01:37.94,Default,,0,0,0,,And, Jim, I want to thank you very much \Nfor all your help with this program. \N
Dialogue: 0,1:01:37.94,1:01:40.48,Default,,0,0,0,,I really, really appreciate it. \N
Dialogue: 0,1:01:40.48,1:01:42.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, before we conclude, \N
Dialogue: 0,1:01:42.52,1:01:45.85,Default,,0,0,0,,we’d like to visit the city of Cuzco in Peru, \N
Dialogue: 0,1:01:45.85,1:01:50.89,Default,,0,0,0,,where we have \Na Remote Translation Office, or RTO.\N
Dialogue: 0,1:01:50.89,1:01:54.00,Default,,0,0,0,,The city of Cuzco is a stopover \Nfor travelers to Machu Picchu, \N
Dialogue: 0,1:01:55.80,1:01:59.93,Default,,0,0,0,,a historic sanctuary \Nof the former Inca Empire, \N
Dialogue: 0,1:01:59.93,1:02:02.44,Default,,0,0,0,,located high up in the mountains. \N
Dialogue: 0,1:02:02.44,1:02:06.27,Default,,0,0,0,,Machu Picchu is an architectural marvel. \N
Dialogue: 0,1:02:06.27,1:02:09.44,Default,,0,0,0,,The design is earthquake resistant. \N
Dialogue: 0,1:02:09.44,1:02:12.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Giant stones were cut so precisely \N
Dialogue: 0,1:02:12.38,1:02:15.58,Default,,0,0,0,,that in many places a piece of paper \N
Dialogue: 0,1:02:15.58,1:02:18.08,Default,,0,0,0,,cannot fit in between them. \N
Dialogue: 0,1:02:18.08,1:02:21.59,Default,,0,0,0,,At such high altitudes, \Nyou can also see llamas, \N
Dialogue: 0,1:02:21.59,1:02:24.89,Default,,0,0,0,,which are raised \Nin the Andes Mountains. \N
Dialogue: 0,1:02:24.89,1:02:27.13,Default,,0,0,0,,The Inca people spoke Quechua, \N
Dialogue: 0,1:02:27.13,1:02:29.13,Default,,0,0,0,,a language that is spoken \N
Dialogue: 0,1:02:29.13,1:02:32.06,Default,,0,0,0,,by millions of Peruvians today.\N
Dialogue: 0,1:02:32.06,1:02:35.00,Default,,0,0,0,,There has been a translation office in Cuzco \N
Dialogue: 0,1:02:35.00,1:02:37.30,Default,,0,0,0,,since 2004, \N
Dialogue: 0,1:02:37.30,1:02:39.31,Default,,0,0,0,,but as the work grew, \N
Dialogue: 0,1:02:39.31,1:02:41.81,Default,,0,0,0,,so did the need for more office space. \N
Dialogue: 0,1:02:41.81,1:02:46.81,Default,,0,0,0,,So in 2016, a new RTO was dedicated. \N
Dialogue: 0,1:02:46.81,1:02:50.88,Default,,0,0,0,,The blessings of the translation work \Nhave been evident. \N
Dialogue: 0,1:02:50.88,1:02:55.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Since the Bible Teach book \Nwas released in Quechua in 2007, \N
Dialogue: 0,1:02:55.52,1:02:57.86,Default,,0,0,0,,the number of publishers increased \N
Dialogue: 0,1:02:57.86,1:03:00.13,Default,,0,0,0,,from about 700 \N
Dialogue: 0,1:03:00.13,1:03:04.16,Default,,0,0,0,,to nearly 1,700 last year. \N
Dialogue: 0,1:03:04.16,1:03:06.10,Default,,0,0,0,,In addition to The Watchtower \N
Dialogue: 0,1:03:06.10,1:03:08.10,Default,,0,0,0,,and the Life and Ministry Meeting Workbook, \N
Dialogue: 0,1:03:08.10,1:03:11.64,Default,,0,0,0,,videos are translated at this office, \N
Dialogue: 0,1:03:11.64,1:03:15.71,Default,,0,0,0,,ranging from JW Broadcasting \Nmonthly programs \N
Dialogue: 0,1:03:15.71,1:03:19.85,Default,,0,0,0,,to episodes of Become Jehovah’s Friend.\N
Dialogue: 0,1:03:19.85,1:03:23.48,Default,,0,0,0,,There are several regions in Peru \Nwhere Quechua is spoken, \N
Dialogue: 0,1:03:23.48,1:03:27.05,Default,,0,0,0,,all with slightly different dialects \Nand expressions. \N
Dialogue: 0,1:03:27.05,1:03:30.29,Default,,0,0,0,,Hence, \Neach translation team \N
Dialogue: 0,1:03:30.29,1:03:33.93,Default,,0,0,0,,has representatives from these areas \N
Dialogue: 0,1:03:33.93,1:03:36.06,Default,,0,0,0,,in order to ensure that the translation \N
Dialogue: 0,1:03:36.06,1:03:38.43,Default,,0,0,0,,is universally understood \N
Dialogue: 0,1:03:38.43,1:03:40.50,Default,,0,0,0,,among Quechua speakers. \N
Dialogue: 0,1:03:40.50,1:03:45.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Approximately 40 brothers \Nand sisters work at the RTO, \N
Dialogue: 0,1:03:45.20,1:03:48.57,Default,,0,0,0,,of which 15 are full-time. \N
Dialogue: 0,1:03:48.57,1:03:50.68,Default,,0,0,0,,In the Cuzco area, \N
Dialogue: 0,1:03:50.68,1:03:54.65,Default,,0,0,0,,there are 28 congregations and 38 groups, \N
Dialogue: 0,1:03:54.65,1:03:58.15,Default,,0,0,0,,with about 2,000 publishers.\N
Dialogue: 0,1:03:58.15,1:04:02.05,Default,,0,0,0,,We love our brothers and sisters \Nin Cuzco very much indeed. \N
Dialogue: 0,1:04:02.05,1:04:03.62,Default,,0,0,0,,And they want you to know \N
Dialogue: 0,1:04:03.62,1:04:05.63,Default,,0,0,0,,how much they love you. \N
Dialogue: 0,1:04:05.63,1:04:07.79,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, until next time, \N
Dialogue: 0,1:04:07.79,1:04:10.63,Default,,0,0,0,,this is JW Broadcasting \N
Dialogue: 0,1:04:10.63,1:04:12.42,Default,,0,0,0,,from the world headquarters \Nof Jehovah’s Witnesses.\N
